     \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(6)4(7)8/h2,5H,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)/t2-,3+/m1/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"(HCN)n\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide oligomer\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN polymer / DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs on Fe3S4 cubane surface sites analogous to [Fe4S4] clusters in modern CO dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase. H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 to formate via a surface-bound formyl intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite's Fe4S4 cubane units are structural analogs of active centers in modern hydrogenase and ferredoxin (White, Bhartia & Russell, Earth Planet. Sci. Lett., 2015). CO2 reduction to formate on FeS/greigite surfaces at alkaline vent conditions is thermodynamically favourable (Shock & Canovas, Science, 1998). Lane & Martin (J. Mol. Evol., 2012) showed that Fe(Ni)S minerals in alkaline vent micropores could concentrate organics ~5000-fold.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction, subseafloor hydrothermal zone\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate undergoes further 2-electron reduction on magnetite surface assisted by Fe0 as strong reductant. The reaction proceeds via surface-bound formyl species to yield formaldehyde, which is released into hydrothermal fluid. Magnetite catalyses Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis of reduced C1 species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite catalyses Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis producing formaldehyde, methanol, and higher aldehydes (reviewed in McCollom & Seewald, Chem. Rev., 2007). Fe0 acts as the terminal electron donor for formate reduction. This connects deep-vent CO2 fixation to aldehyde feedstocks needed for Strecker synthesis at the surface.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of C1-C2 aldehydes from HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"copper cyanide minerals (CuCN)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide complexes\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), shallow evaporitic pool, phosphate buffer ~pH 7\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV light drives Cu(I)-catalysed photoredox cycling of HCN with H2S as reductant. Sequential Kiliani-Fischer reductive homologation converts HCN first to formaldehyde, then to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde via interconversion of cyanohydrins and aldehydes. Each homologation step involves HCN addition to form a cyanohydrin, followed by photoreduction of the nitrile to an aldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) demonstrated each step experimentally: UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide complexes with H2S converts HCN to formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde through photoredox cycling. Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) placed this within the broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism producing amino acid and ribonucleotide precursors simultaneously.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-type aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)2 or borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline evaporitic pool, borate stabilises sugar intermediates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo base-catalysed aldol self-condensation: the umpolung step generates a nucleophilic carbanion from one HCHO that attacks a second HCHO, yielding glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO). Borate minerals stabilise the product against retro-aldol and Cannizzaro side reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction (Butlerow, 1861) converts formaldehyde to C2-C6 sugars under alkaline conditions. Borate minerals stabilise sugars including glycolaldehyde and ribose (Ricardo et al., Science, 2004). Glycolaldehyde is the crucial branch point between sugar and amino acid chemistry (Patel et al., Nature Chemistry, 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions; 2-aminothiazole may selectively sequester glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from complex mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of formaldehyde-derived enolate to the carbonyl of glycolaldehyde produces glyceraldehyde. Borate complexation protects the vicinal diol of glyceraldehyde from degradation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyceraldehyde is central to Sutherland's ribonucleotide synthesis and directly reacts with HCN and NH3 to form the threonine aminonitrile (Patel et al., Nature Chemistry, 2015). Islam, Bucar & Powner (Nature Chemistry, 2017) showed that 2-aminothiazole selectively sequesters glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from complex mixtures.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetaldehyde cyanohydrin formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (spontaneous in presence of HCN)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"facile nucleophilic addition, prebiotically spontaneous\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide ion (CN\u207b) attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde in a nucleophilic addition, yielding 2-hydroxypropanenitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin / lactonitrile). The reaction is rapid and nearly quantitative at mildly basic pH.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) demonstrated that acetaldehyde reacts with HCN to form acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as the key intermediate en route to lactaldehyde. This is a textbook cyanohydrin formation that proceeds spontaneously in aqueous HCN.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"copper cyanide minerals (CuCN)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), H2S as sacrificial reductant, 19% yield after 2 hours\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV excitation of Cu(I)-cyanide complex generates a photoexcited state that abstracts an electron from H2S. The resulting reducing equivalent is transferred to the nitrile group of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, reducing it through an imine intermediate to the corresponding aldehyde (lactaldehyde). Sulfur is oxidized to elemental sulfur or polysulfides.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) demonstrated that photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin yields lactaldehyde at 19% yield after 2 hours of UV irradiation with Cu(I) cyanide and H2S. This is the key step specific to the threonine Strecker pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surfaces for concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, one-pot Strecker conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base) via nucleophilic addition-elimination. HCN then adds to the electrophilic carbon of the imine (aminonitrile formation). The product 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile (threonine aminonitrile) forms as a racemic mixture of threonine and allothreonine diastereomers (~1:1).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) demonstrated this classic Strecker chemistry: lactaldehyde + NH3 + HCN yields 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile. Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) identified this aminonitrile as one of four amino acid precursors arising as 'inevitable by-products' of the cyanosulfidic protometabolism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, alternative entry into Strecker aminonitrile\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde reacts with NH3 to form the corresponding imine. HCN addition yields 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile (threonine aminonitrile) plus the 2-amino-2,3-dihydroxypropanenitrile (serine aminonitrile). The C3 glyceraldehyde route provides a parallel entry to the same threonine aminonitrile as the C3 lactaldehyde route.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) showed that glyceraldehyde + NH3 + HCN directly yields the threonine aminonitrile, making glyceraldehyde 'perhaps the single most important branch point connecting RNA and protein precursor chemistry'. This provides a second entry from the sugar branch of the cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (acid or base catalysis)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH-dependent hydrolysis; proceeds through amide intermediate; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two-step hydrolysis: the nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile is first hydrated to form the corresponding amide (threonine amide), which is then hydrolysed to threonine. Both steps are accelerated under mildly acidic or basic conditions and by elevated temperature.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Standard nitrile-to-acid hydrolysis completes the Strecker synthesis. This is the terminal step described by Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) and Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015). The hydrolysis is thermally promoted and occurs spontaneously in warm aqueous solution. Threonine instability (Truong et al., Icarus, 2019) constrains the maximum temperature for this step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycine and acetaldehyde to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surface or divalent metal ions\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"thermodynamically unfavourable; requires high glycine concentration or catalytic assistance; produces both threonine and allothreonine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-carbon of glycine is deprotonated to form a nucleophilic carbanion (facilitated by metal-ion coordination or Schiff-base activation). This attacks the carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde in an aldol addition, forming a new C\u2013C bond and generating threonine/allothreonine. The retro-reaction (threonine aldolase cleavage) defines the structural relationship.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The biological retro-aldol cleavage of threonine (catalysed by threonine aldolases) yields glycine + acetaldehyde (Fesko, Appl. Microbiol. Biotechnol., 2016). The reverse aldol condensation is thermodynamically unfavourable but conceptually defines the simplest route. Koga & Naraoka (ACS Earth Space Chem., 2022) demonstrated related ammonia-aldehyde chemistry producing hydroxy amino acids from labeled aldehydes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"one of the most facile Strecker reactions; glycine is the dominant amino acid in Miller-Urey experiments\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form methyleneimine (H2C=NH). HCN adds across the C=N bond to form aminoacetonitrile (H2NCH2CN), which hydrolyses to glycine. This is the simplest possible Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycine is the most abundant amino acid in Miller-Urey spark discharge experiments (Ring, Wolman, Friedmann & Miller, PNAS, 1972) and forms readily via the Strecker mechanism from formaldehyde + NH3 + HCN. This reaction feeds the aldol condensation pathway to threonine (rxn_011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ammonium carbonate (NH4HCO3) from NH3 + CO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"hydantoin acts as thermodynamic sink; more stable than aminonitrile intermediate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with HCN to form the cyanohydrin, which reacts with NH3 to form the aminonitrile. In the presence of CO2 (as carbonate/bicarbonate), the aminonitrile cyclises to form 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin via carbamoylation and intramolecular cyclisation. The hydantoin ring is a thermodynamic sink relative to the open-chain aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (Nature Chemistry, 2022) demonstrated the Bucherer-Bergs pathway for several keto acids to amino acids via hydantoin intermediates. Hydantoins have been detected in carbonaceous chondrites (Lerner & Cooper, Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta, 2005), consistent with this pathway operating in meteorite parent bodies. The hydantoin provides kinetic trapping advantages over direct Strecker.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydantoin hydrolysis to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (base-promoted hydrolysis)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"two-step ring opening: first to N-carbamoyl amino acid, then to free amino acid + CO2 + NH3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base-catalysed hydrolysis of the hydantoin ring proceeds in two steps: (1) ring opening at the less hindered C2\u2013N3 bond to yield N-carbamoyl-threonine, then (2) decarbamoylation to release free threonine, CO2, and NH3. Elevated temperature accelerates both steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2022) demonstrated that hydantoins hydrolyse to free amino acids under mild prebiotic conditions. This pathway parallels extant biosynthetic routes and provides a robust alternative to direct aminonitrile hydrolysis. The hydantoin intermediate may persist longer than the aminonitrile, providing a slow-release reservoir for threonine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"CO-driven pyruvate synthesis on iron-sulfide surfaces\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS / NiS coprecipitates\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wachtershauserian iron-sulfur world conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO binds to FeS surface sites and undergoes sequential carbonylation and reduction. Insertion of CO into surface-bound methyl (from prior CH4 or CO reduction) yields a surface-bound acetyl, which is carbonylated again and hydrated to form pyruvate. The mineral surface provides both the catalytic sites and the reducing equivalents from FeS oxidation to FeS2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cody, Boctor & Hazen (Science, 2000) showed that carbonylated iron-sulfur compounds produce pyruvate from CO and FeS at hydrothermal conditions. Huber & Wachtershaeuser (Science, 2006) demonstrated CO-dependent formation of alpha-hydroxy and alpha-amino acids on Ni-Fe precipitates at 80-120\u00b0C.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Chain elongation of pyruvate to alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe(Ni)S mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"aldol-type chain elongation on mineral surface; formaldehyde adds to pyruvate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes aldol-type condensation with formaldehyde on the mineral surface. The enolate of pyruvate (stabilized by mineral surface coordination) attacks formaldehyde, producing 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate (alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate). The mineral surface provides Lewis acid activation of both substrates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & Wachtershaeuser (Science, 2006) demonstrated that Ni-Fe precipitates catalyse C-C bond formation from simple precursors under hydrothermal conditions. Copley, Smith & Morowitz (PNAS, 2005) proposed that alpha-keto acids formed through chain-elongation reactions on mineral surfaces in a proto-metabolic network. The pyruvate-to-ketobutyrate step parallels biological threonine dehydratase (in reverse).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ or Ni catalysts\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8, H2 as reductant; analogous to Muchowska et al. Fe(0)-promoted reductive amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-keto group of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate undergoes nucleophilic addition of NH3 to form the corresponding imine (Schiff base). The imine is then reduced by H2 (activated on the mineral surface or by dissolved Fe2+) to yield threonine. The reaction is analogous to biological transamination but uses abiotic reductants.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska, Varma & Moran (Nature, 2019) demonstrated that Fe2+ promotes reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids at 70\u00b0C. Kaur et al. (Chem, 2024) extended this to H2-driven reductive amination over nickel catalysts at 22\u00b0C and pH 8. While threonine's specific keto acid was not explicitly tested, the principle is established for structurally analogous substrates.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN and higher polymers\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"250-300K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation or base catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"concentrated HCN solutions (>0.01M); can also proceed during eutectic freezing at -20\u00b0C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN molecules undergo sequential nucleophilic additions: 2 HCN \u2192 aminomalononitrile; 4 HCN \u2192 diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN). Further polymerization yields dark heterogeneous HCN polymers incorporating both C-C and C-N bonds. Amino acid side chains are embedded within the polymer backbone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano & Osuna-Esteban (Life, 2013) reviewed 24 experimental conditions and found that 12 of the 20 proteinogenic amino acids, including threonine, were detected in HCN polymer hydrolysates. Miyakawa et al. (Origins Life Evol. Biosph., 2002) froze NH4CN solutions for 25 years and obtained amino acids, showing cold environments drive HCN oligomerisation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of HCN oligomers to amino acids including threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"acid or base hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"prolonged hydrolysis (days to weeks); yields complex mixture with glycine dominant; threonine present at trace levels\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acid or base-catalysed hydrolysis cleaves amide, nitrile, and imine bonds within the HCN polymer, releasing embedded amino acids including glycine (dominant), alanine, aspartate, and threonine. Yields depend on polymer structure and hydrolysis conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano & Osuna-Esteban (Life, 2013) confirmed threonine among 12 proteinogenic amino acids detected in HCN polymer hydrolysates across 24 experimental conditions. This provides a non-specific but robust route to threonine from the simplest nitrogen-containing prebiotic feedstock.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonia-aldehyde synthesis of hydroxy amino acids\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (mineral-assisted concentration)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"aldehyde + ammonia chemistry without HCN; produces families of C3-C4 hydroxy amino acids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde react with ammonia through a series of aldol, Mannich-type, and reductive amination steps to produce C3 and C4 hydroxy amino acids including threonine, allothreonine, serine, and homoserine. The reaction network branches through multiple aldol/amino intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Koga & Naraoka (ACS Earth Space Chem., 2022) demonstrated that 13C-labeled aldehydes (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde) reacting with ammonia in aqueous solution produced families of hydroxy amino acids including C3 and C4 structural isomers matching distributions in CM and CR carbonaceous chondrites. This ammonia-aldehyde chemistry provides a route to threonine without requiring HCN.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"The primary experimentally validated route: HCN photoredox generates acetaldehyde, which forms a cyanohydrin with HCN, then is photoreduced to lactaldehyde. Strecker reaction with NH3 and HCN yields threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyses to threonine. Complete pathway demonstrated by Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glyceraldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative cyanosulfidic entry: HCN photoredox generates formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde, which undergo aldol condensation to glyceraldehyde. Strecker reaction of glyceraldehyde with NH3 and HCN yields threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyses to threonine. Connects RNA and amino acid precursor chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 to formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Deep-vent CO2 fixation on greigite produces formate, reduced to formaldehyde on magnetite. Formaldehyde undergoes formose-type condensation at the surface to glycolaldehyde, then glyceraldehyde. Strecker aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis yield threonine. Cross-environment pathway linking Hydrothermal and Surface.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 to formaldehyde to lactaldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate and formaldehyde, transported to surface where cyanosulfidic chemistry converts it through acetaldehyde and cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde. Strecker reaction completes threonine synthesis. Full Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical chain.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycine + acetaldehyde aldol condensation\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycine (from Strecker synthesis of formaldehyde) condenses with acetaldehyde (from cyanosulfidic photoredox) in an aldol reaction to form threonine directly. Thermodynamically unfavourable but represents the simplest structural disconnection. Reverse of biological threonine aldolase.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway via lactaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde (from cyanohydrin photoreduction) reacts with HCN, NH3, and CO2 to form 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin, which acts as a thermodynamic sink. Hydrolysis releases threonine. Hydantoin intermediates detected in carbonaceous chondrites.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Iron-sulfur world keto acid reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO reacts with FeS to generate pyruvate under hydrothermal conditions. Chain elongation with formaldehyde produces alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate, which undergoes Fe2+-promoted reductive amination to threonine. Entirely hydrothermal pathway analogous to reverse citric acid cycle.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization and hydrolysis\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN polymerises under UV or eutectic freezing conditions to form DAMN and higher oligomers. Prolonged hydrolysis releases complex amino acid mixtures including threonine. Low-selectivity but robust pathway; threonine detected across 24 experimental conditions in HCN polymer hydrolysates.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 to keto acid to reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced to formate then formaldehyde at hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde feeds chain elongation of pyruvate (from CO + FeS) to alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate. Reductive amination with NH3 and H2 yields threonine. Fully hydrothermal pathway combining carbon fixation and amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonia-aldehyde hydroxy amino acid pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde (from cyanosulfidic photoredox or formose chemistry) react with ammonia in aqueous solution to produce C4 hydroxy amino acids including threonine. HCN-independent route matching amino acid distributions in CM and CR carbonaceous chondrites.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrogen cyanide: universal C1/N source feeding Strecker, Bucherer-Bergs, cyanohydrin, oligomerisation, and cyanosulfidic photoredox pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde: central C1 building block produced by both hydrothermal CO2 reduction and cyanosulfidic photoredox; feeds formose sugars, Strecker glycine, and keto acid chain elongation\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde: key C2 aldehyde produced by cyanosulfidic chemistry; branches to lactaldehyde (via cyanohydrin), aldol with glycine, and ammonia-aldehyde pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde: the aldehyde specific to threonine Strecker synthesis; produced by UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin at 19% yield; feeds both Strecker and Bucherer-Bergs routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Threonine aminonitrile (2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile): convergence point of lactaldehyde and glyceraldehyde Strecker routes; single hydrolysis step to threonine\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "Ten convergent pathways connect simple C1\u2013C2 feedstocks (CO\u2082, HCN, CO, H\u2082, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) to threonine across three prebiotic environments. Hydrothermal vents provide CO\u2082 reduction to formate/formaldehyde on greigite/magnetite and iron-sulfur-catalysed keto acid synthesis. Surface pools host cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland 2013; Patel et al. 2015) generating formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and lactaldehyde, which undergo Strecker or Bucherer-Bergs reactions to threonine aminonitrile or hydantoin. Biochemical-stage hydrolysis, aldol condensation, and HCN oligomer decomposition complete the network. Five hub molecules (HCN, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, threonine aminonitrile) create a densely interconnected bipartite graph with multiple redundant routes.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "acetaldehyde cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-3(5)2-4/h3,5H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(6)4(7)8/h2,5H,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)/t2-,3+/m1/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "(HCN)n", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide oligomer", "common_name": "HCN polymer / DAMN", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO2 adsorbs on Fe3S4 cubane surface sites analogous to [Fe4S4] clusters in modern CO dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase. H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 to formate via a surface-bound formyl intermediate.", "reasoning": "Greigite's Fe4S4 cubane units are structural analogs of active centers in modern hydrogenase and ferredoxin (White, Bhartia & Russell, Earth Planet. Sci. Lett., 2015). CO2 reduction to formate on FeS/greigite surfaces at alkaline vent conditions is thermodynamically favourable (Shock & Canovas, Science, 1998). Lane & Martin (J. Mol. Evol., 2012) showed that Fe(Ni)S minerals in alkaline vent micropores could concentrate organics ~5000-fold."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction, subseafloor hydrothermal zone"}, "mechanism": "Formate undergoes further 2-electron reduction on magnetite surface assisted by Fe0 as strong reductant. The reaction proceeds via surface-bound formyl species to yield formaldehyde, which is released into hydrothermal fluid. Magnetite catalyses Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis of reduced C1 species.", "reasoning": "Magnetite catalyses Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis producing formaldehyde, methanol, and higher aldehydes (reviewed in McCollom & Seewald, Chem. Rev., 2007). Fe0 acts as the terminal electron donor for formate reduction. This connects deep-vent CO2 fixation to aldehyde feedstocks needed for Strecker synthesis at the surface."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of C1-C2 aldehydes from HCN", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["copper cyanide minerals (CuCN)", "stibnite (Sb2S3)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide complexes", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (254 nm), shallow evaporitic pool, phosphate buffer ~pH 7"}, "mechanism": "UV light drives Cu(I)-catalysed photoredox cycling of HCN with H2S as reductant. Sequential Kiliani-Fischer reductive homologation converts HCN first to formaldehyde, then to glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde via interconversion of cyanohydrins and aldehydes. Each homologation step involves HCN addition to form a cyanohydrin, followed by photoreduction of the nitrile to an aldehyde.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) demonstrated each step experimentally: UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide complexes with H2S converts HCN to formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde through photoredox cycling. Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) placed this within the broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism producing amino acid and ribonucleotide precursors simultaneously."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formose-type aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)2 or borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline evaporitic pool, borate stabilises sugar intermediates"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo base-catalysed aldol self-condensation: the umpolung step generates a nucleophilic carbanion from one HCHO that attacks a second HCHO, yielding glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO). Borate minerals stabilise the product against retro-aldol and Cannizzaro side reactions.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction (Butlerow, 1861) converts formaldehyde to C2-C6 sugars under alkaline conditions. Borate minerals stabilise sugars including glycolaldehyde and ribose (Ricardo et al., Science, 2004). Glycolaldehyde is the crucial branch point between sugar and amino acid chemistry (Patel et al., Nature Chemistry, 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline conditions; 2-aminothiazole may selectively sequester glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from complex mixtures"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of formaldehyde-derived enolate to the carbonyl of glycolaldehyde produces glyceraldehyde. Borate complexation protects the vicinal diol of glyceraldehyde from degradation.", "reasoning": "Glyceraldehyde is central to Sutherland's ribonucleotide synthesis and directly reacts with HCN and NH3 to form the threonine aminonitrile (Patel et al., Nature Chemistry, 2015). Islam, Bucar & Powner (Nature Chemistry, 2017) showed that 2-aminothiazole selectively sequesters glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from complex mixtures."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Acetaldehyde cyanohydrin formation", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (spontaneous in presence of HCN)", "aqueous": true, "other": "facile nucleophilic addition, prebiotically spontaneous"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide ion (CN\u207b) attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde in a nucleophilic addition, yielding 2-hydroxypropanenitrile (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin / lactonitrile). The reaction is rapid and nearly quantitative at mildly basic pH.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) demonstrated that acetaldehyde reacts with HCN to form acetaldehyde cyanohydrin as the key intermediate en route to lactaldehyde. This is a textbook cyanohydrin formation that proceeds spontaneously in aqueous HCN."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["copper cyanide minerals (CuCN)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photocatalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (254 nm), H2S as sacrificial reductant, 19% yield after 2 hours"}, "mechanism": "UV excitation of Cu(I)-cyanide complex generates a photoexcited state that abstracts an electron from H2S. The resulting reducing equivalent is transferred to the nitrile group of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, reducing it through an imine intermediate to the corresponding aldehyde (lactaldehyde). Sulfur is oxidized to elemental sulfur or polysulfides.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) demonstrated that photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin yields lactaldehyde at 19% yield after 2 hours of UV irradiation with Cu(I) cyanide and H2S. This is the key step specific to the threonine Strecker pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surfaces for concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, one-pot Strecker conditions"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base) via nucleophilic addition-elimination. HCN then adds to the electrophilic carbon of the imine (aminonitrile formation). The product 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile (threonine aminonitrile) forms as a racemic mixture of threonine and allothreonine diastereomers (~1:1).", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) demonstrated this classic Strecker chemistry: lactaldehyde + NH3 + HCN yields 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile. Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) identified this aminonitrile as one of four amino acid precursors arising as 'inevitable by-products' of the cyanosulfidic protometabolism."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, alternative entry into Strecker aminonitrile"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde reacts with NH3 to form the corresponding imine. HCN addition yields 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile (threonine aminonitrile) plus the 2-amino-2,3-dihydroxypropanenitrile (serine aminonitrile). The C3 glyceraldehyde route provides a parallel entry to the same threonine aminonitrile as the C3 lactaldehyde route.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) showed that glyceraldehyde + NH3 + HCN directly yields the threonine aminonitrile, making glyceraldehyde 'perhaps the single most important branch point connecting RNA and protein precursor chemistry'. This provides a second entry from the sugar branch of the cyanosulfidic network."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (acid or base catalysis)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH-dependent hydrolysis; proceeds through amide intermediate; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine"}, "mechanism": "Two-step hydrolysis: the nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile is first hydrated to form the corresponding amide (threonine amide), which is then hydrolysed to threonine. Both steps are accelerated under mildly acidic or basic conditions and by elevated temperature.", "reasoning": "Standard nitrile-to-acid hydrolysis completes the Strecker synthesis. This is the terminal step described by Ritson & Sutherland (Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 2013) and Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015). The hydrolysis is thermally promoted and occurs spontaneously in warm aqueous solution. Threonine instability (Truong et al., Icarus, 2019) constrains the maximum temperature for this step."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycine and acetaldehyde to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surface or divalent metal ions", "aqueous": true, "other": "thermodynamically unfavourable; requires high glycine concentration or catalytic assistance; produces both threonine and allothreonine"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-carbon of glycine is deprotonated to form a nucleophilic carbanion (facilitated by metal-ion coordination or Schiff-base activation). This attacks the carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde in an aldol addition, forming a new C\u2013C bond and generating threonine/allothreonine. The retro-reaction (threonine aldolase cleavage) defines the structural relationship.", "reasoning": "The biological retro-aldol cleavage of threonine (catalysed by threonine aldolases) yields glycine + acetaldehyde (Fesko, Appl. Microbiol. Biotechnol., 2016). The reverse aldol condensation is thermodynamically unfavourable but conceptually defines the simplest route. Koga & Naraoka (ACS Earth Space Chem., 2022) demonstrated related ammonia-aldehyde chemistry producing hydroxy amino acids from labeled aldehydes."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "one of the most facile Strecker reactions; glycine is the dominant amino acid in Miller-Urey experiments"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form methyleneimine (H2C=NH). HCN adds across the C=N bond to form aminoacetonitrile (H2NCH2CN), which hydrolyses to glycine. This is the simplest possible Strecker synthesis.", "reasoning": "Glycine is the most abundant amino acid in Miller-Urey spark discharge experiments (Ring, Wolman, Friedmann & Miller, PNAS, 1972) and forms readily via the Strecker mechanism from formaldehyde + NH3 + HCN. This reaction feeds the aldol condensation pathway to threonine (rxn_011)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ammonium carbonate (NH4HCO3) from NH3 + CO2", "aqueous": true, "other": "hydantoin acts as thermodynamic sink; more stable than aminonitrile intermediate"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with HCN to form the cyanohydrin, which reacts with NH3 to form the aminonitrile. In the presence of CO2 (as carbonate/bicarbonate), the aminonitrile cyclises to form 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin via carbamoylation and intramolecular cyclisation. The hydantoin ring is a thermodynamic sink relative to the open-chain aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (Nature Chemistry, 2022) demonstrated the Bucherer-Bergs pathway for several keto acids to amino acids via hydantoin intermediates. Hydantoins have been detected in carbonaceous chondrites (Lerner & Cooper, Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta, 2005), consistent with this pathway operating in meteorite parent bodies. The hydantoin provides kinetic trapping advantages over direct Strecker."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydantoin hydrolysis to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (base-promoted hydrolysis)", "aqueous": true, "other": "two-step ring opening: first to N-carbamoyl amino acid, then to free amino acid + CO2 + NH3"}, "mechanism": "Base-catalysed hydrolysis of the hydantoin ring proceeds in two steps: (1) ring opening at the less hindered C2\u2013N3 bond to yield N-carbamoyl-threonine, then (2) decarbamoylation to release free threonine, CO2, and NH3. Elevated temperature accelerates both steps.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2022) demonstrated that hydantoins hydrolyse to free amino acids under mild prebiotic conditions. This pathway parallels extant biosynthetic routes and provides a robust alternative to direct aminonitrile hydrolysis. The hydantoin intermediate may persist longer than the aminonitrile, providing a slow-release reservoir for threonine."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "CO-driven pyruvate synthesis on iron-sulfide surfaces", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS / NiS coprecipitates", "aqueous": true, "other": "Wachtershauserian iron-sulfur world conditions"}, "mechanism": "CO binds to FeS surface sites and undergoes sequential carbonylation and reduction. Insertion of CO into surface-bound methyl (from prior CH4 or CO reduction) yields a surface-bound acetyl, which is carbonylated again and hydrated to form pyruvate. The mineral surface provides both the catalytic sites and the reducing equivalents from FeS oxidation to FeS2.", "reasoning": "Cody, Boctor & Hazen (Science, 2000) showed that carbonylated iron-sulfur compounds produce pyruvate from CO and FeS at hydrothermal conditions. Huber & Wachtershaeuser (Science, 2006) demonstrated CO-dependent formation of alpha-hydroxy and alpha-amino acids on Ni-Fe precipitates at 80-120\u00b0C."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Chain elongation of pyruvate to alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe(Ni)S mineral surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "aldol-type chain elongation on mineral surface; formaldehyde adds to pyruvate"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes aldol-type condensation with formaldehyde on the mineral surface. The enolate of pyruvate (stabilized by mineral surface coordination) attacks formaldehyde, producing 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate (alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate). The mineral surface provides Lewis acid activation of both substrates.", "reasoning": "Huber & Wachtershaeuser (Science, 2006) demonstrated that Ni-Fe precipitates catalyse C-C bond formation from simple precursors under hydrothermal conditions. Copley, Smith & Morowitz (PNAS, 2005) proposed that alpha-keto acids formed through chain-elongation reactions on mineral surfaces in a proto-metabolic network. The pyruvate-to-ketobutyrate step parallels biological threonine dehydratase (in reverse)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "Fe2+ or Ni catalysts", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8, H2 as reductant; analogous to Muchowska et al. Fe(0)-promoted reductive amination"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-keto group of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate undergoes nucleophilic addition of NH3 to form the corresponding imine (Schiff base). The imine is then reduced by H2 (activated on the mineral surface or by dissolved Fe2+) to yield threonine. The reaction is analogous to biological transamination but uses abiotic reductants.", "reasoning": "Muchowska, Varma & Moran (Nature, 2019) demonstrated that Fe2+ promotes reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids at 70\u00b0C. Kaur et al. (Chem, 2024) extended this to H2-driven reductive amination over nickel catalysts at 22\u00b0C and pH 8. While threonine's specific keto acid was not explicitly tested, the principle is established for structurally analogous substrates."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "HCN oligomerization to DAMN and higher polymers", "inputs": ["mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "250-300K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV irradiation or base catalysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "concentrated HCN solutions (>0.01M); can also proceed during eutectic freezing at -20\u00b0C"}, "mechanism": "HCN molecules undergo sequential nucleophilic additions: 2 HCN \u2192 aminomalononitrile; 4 HCN \u2192 diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN). Further polymerization yields dark heterogeneous HCN polymers incorporating both C-C and C-N bonds. Amino acid side chains are embedded within the polymer backbone.", "reasoning": "Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano & Osuna-Esteban (Life, 2013) reviewed 24 experimental conditions and found that 12 of the 20 proteinogenic amino acids, including threonine, were detected in HCN polymer hydrolysates. Miyakawa et al. (Origins Life Evol. Biosph., 2002) froze NH4CN solutions for 25 years and obtained amino acids, showing cold environments drive HCN oligomerisation."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Hydrolysis of HCN oligomers to amino acids including threonine", "inputs": ["mol_021", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "acid or base hydrolysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "prolonged hydrolysis (days to weeks); yields complex mixture with glycine dominant; threonine present at trace levels"}, "mechanism": "Acid or base-catalysed hydrolysis cleaves amide, nitrile, and imine bonds within the HCN polymer, releasing embedded amino acids including glycine (dominant), alanine, aspartate, and threonine. Yields depend on polymer structure and hydrolysis conditions.", "reasoning": "Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano & Osuna-Esteban (Life, 2013) confirmed threonine among 12 proteinogenic amino acids detected in HCN polymer hydrolysates across 24 experimental conditions. This provides a non-specific but robust route to threonine from the simplest nitrogen-containing prebiotic feedstock."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Ammonia-aldehyde synthesis of hydroxy amino acids", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (mineral-assisted concentration)", "aqueous": true, "other": "aldehyde + ammonia chemistry without HCN; produces families of C3-C4 hydroxy amino acids"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde react with ammonia through a series of aldol, Mannich-type, and reductive amination steps to produce C3 and C4 hydroxy amino acids including threonine, allothreonine, serine, and homoserine. The reaction network branches through multiple aldol/amino intermediates.", "reasoning": "Koga & Naraoka (ACS Earth Space Chem., 2022) demonstrated that 13C-labeled aldehydes (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde) reacting with ammonia in aqueous solution produced families of hydroxy amino acids including C3 and C4 structural isomers matching distributions in CM and CR carbonaceous chondrites. This ammonia-aldehyde chemistry provides a route to threonine without requiring HCN."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde Strecker route", "description": "The primary experimentally validated route: HCN photoredox generates acetaldehyde, which forms a cyanohydrin with HCN, then is photoreduced to lactaldehyde. Strecker reaction with NH3 and HCN yields threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyses to threonine. Complete pathway demonstrated by Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanosulfidic glyceraldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Alternative cyanosulfidic entry: HCN photoredox generates formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde, which undergo aldol condensation to glyceraldehyde. Strecker reaction of glyceraldehyde with NH3 and HCN yields threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyses to threonine. Connects RNA and amino acid precursor chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 to formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde route", "description": "Deep-vent CO2 fixation on greigite produces formate, reduced to formaldehyde on magnetite. Formaldehyde undergoes formose-type condensation at the surface to glycolaldehyde, then glyceraldehyde. Strecker aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis yield threonine. Cross-environment pathway linking Hydrothermal and Surface.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 to formaldehyde to lactaldehyde route", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate and formaldehyde, transported to surface where cyanosulfidic chemistry converts it through acetaldehyde and cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde. Strecker reaction completes threonine synthesis. Full Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical chain.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Glycine + acetaldehyde aldol condensation", "description": "Glycine (from Strecker synthesis of formaldehyde) condenses with acetaldehyde (from cyanosulfidic photoredox) in an aldol reaction to form threonine directly. Thermodynamically unfavourable but represents the simplest structural disconnection. Reverse of biological threonine aldolase.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_012", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway via lactaldehyde", "description": "Lactaldehyde (from cyanohydrin photoreduction) reacts with HCN, NH3, and CO2 to form 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin, which acts as a thermodynamic sink. Hydrolysis releases threonine. Hydantoin intermediates detected in carbonaceous chondrites.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_013", "mol_012", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Iron-sulfur world keto acid reductive amination", "description": "CO reacts with FeS to generate pyruvate under hydrothermal conditions. Chain elongation with formaldehyde produces alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate, which undergoes Fe2+-promoted reductive amination to threonine. Entirely hydrothermal pathway analogous to reverse citric acid cycle.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_020", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "HCN oligomerization and hydrolysis", "description": "HCN polymerises under UV or eutectic freezing conditions to form DAMN and higher oligomers. Prolonged hydrolysis releases complex amino acid mixtures including threonine. Low-selectivity but robust pathway; threonine detected across 24 experimental conditions in HCN polymer hydrolysates.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_021"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 to keto acid to reductive amination", "description": "CO2 is reduced to formate then formaldehyde at hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde feeds chain elongation of pyruvate (from CO + FeS) to alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate. Reductive amination with NH3 and H2 yields threonine. Fully hydrothermal pathway combining carbon fixation and amination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_020", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Ammonia-aldehyde hydroxy amino acid pathway", "description": "Glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde (from cyanosulfidic photoredox or formose chemistry) react with ammonia in aqueous solution to produce C4 hydroxy amino acids including threonine. HCN-independent route matching amino acid distributions in CM and CR carbonaceous chondrites.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_003", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_014"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_003", "description": "Hydrogen cyanide: universal C1/N source feeding Strecker, Bucherer-Bergs, cyanohydrin, oligomerisation, and cyanosulfidic photoredox pathways", "incoming_reactions": [], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_018"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Formaldehyde: central C1 building block produced by both hydrothermal CO2 reduction and cyanosulfidic photoredox; feeds formose sugars, Strecker glycine, and keto acid chain elongation", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_012", "rxn_016"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "Acetaldehyde: key C2 aldehyde produced by cyanosulfidic chemistry; branches to lactaldehyde (via cyanohydrin), aldol with glycine, and ammonia-aldehyde pathways", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_011", "rxn_020"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Lactaldehyde: the aldehyde specific to threonine Strecker synthesis; produced by UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin at 19% yield; feeds both Strecker and Bucherer-Bergs routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Threonine aminonitrile (2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile): convergence point of lactaldehyde and glyceraldehyde Strecker routes; single hydrolysis step to threonine", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 429659.117937088, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T20:35:27.945298", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: Ten convergent pathways connect simple C1\u2013C2 feedstocks (CO\u2082, HCN, CO, H\u2082, NH\u2083, H\u2082S) to threonine across three prebiotic environments. Hydrothermal vents provide CO\u2082 reduction to formate/formaldehyde on greigite/magnetite and iron-sulfur-catalysed keto acid synthesis. Surface pools host cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry (Ritson & Sutherland 2013; Patel et al. 2015) generating formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and lactaldehyde, which undergo Strecker or Bucherer-Bergs reactions to threonine aminonitrile or hydantoin. Biochemical-stage hydrolysis, aldol condensation, and HCN oligomer decomposition complete the network. Five hub molecules (HCN, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, threonine aminonitrile) create a densely interconnected bipartite graph with multiple redundant routes.\n\nMOLECULES (21 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_005: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_006: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_007: CHO2- (formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H6O3 (glyceraldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C3H6O2 (lactaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H5NO (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H8N2O (threonine aminonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C2H5NO2 (glycine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C5H8N2O3 (5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C4H6O4 (alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_018: C4H9NO3 (threonine) [target]\n  - mol_019: CO (carbon monoxide) [starting]\n  - mol_020: C3H4O3 (pyruvate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_021: (HCN)n (HCN polymer / DAMN) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (20 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_007, mol_002 -> mol_008 (Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_003, mol_005, mol_006 -> mol_008, mol_009, mol_010 (Cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of C1-C2 aldehydes from HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_008 -> mol_009 (Formose-type aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_008, mol_009 -> mol_011 (Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_010, mol_003 -> mol_013 (Acetaldehyde cyanohydrin formation) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_013, mol_005 -> mol_012 (UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_012, mol_004, mol_003 -> mol_014 (Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_011, mol_004, mol_003 -> mol_014 (Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_014, mol_006 -> mol_018 (Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_011: mol_015, mol_010 -> mol_018 (Aldol condensation of glycine and acetaldehyde to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_008, mol_004, mol_003 -> mol_015 (Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_012, mol_003, mol_004, mol_001 -> mol_016 (Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_016, mol_006 -> mol_018 (Hydantoin hydrolysis to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_015: mol_019, mol_005 -> mol_020 (CO-driven pyruvate synthesis on iron-sulfide surfaces) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_016: mol_020, mol_008 -> mol_017 (Chain elongation of pyruvate to alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_017: mol_017, mol_004, mol_002 -> mol_018 (Reductive amination of alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate to threonine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_018: mol_003 -> mol_021 (HCN oligomerization to DAMN and higher polymers) [Surface]\n  - rxn_019: mol_021, mol_006 -> mol_018, mol_015 (Hydrolysis of HCN oligomers to amino acids including threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_020: mol_009, mol_010, mol_004 -> mol_018 (Ammonia-aldehyde synthesis of hydroxy amino acids) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde Strecker route (5 steps)\n  - P2: Cyanosulfidic glyceraldehyde Strecker route (4 steps)\n  - P3: Hydrothermal CO2 to formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde route (6 steps)\n  - P4: Hydrothermal CO2 to formaldehyde to lactaldehyde route (7 steps)\n  - P5: Glycine + acetaldehyde aldol condensation (3 steps)\n  - P6: Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway via lactaldehyde (5 steps)\n  - P7: Iron-sulfur world keto acid reductive amination (3 steps)\n  - P8: HCN oligomerization and hydrolysis (2 steps)\n  - P9: Hydrothermal CO2 to keto acid to reductive amination (5 steps)\n  - P10: Ammonia-aldehyde hydroxy amino acid pathway (2 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_003, mol_008, mol_010, mol_012, mol_014\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of threonine: routes, evidence, and unsolved puzzles\n\n**Threonine emerges as one of the most prebiotically accessible yet paradoxically fragile proteinogenic amino acids.** The cyanosulfidic chemistry developed by Sutherland and colleagues demonstrates that threonine's Strecker precursor forms as an \"inevitable by-product\" of the same HCN photoredox chemistry that generates ribonucleotide building blocks \u2014 linking amino acid and RNA origins in a single reaction network (Patel et al., *Nature Chemistry*, 2015). Yet threonine's \u03b2-hydroxyl group renders it among the least stable amino acids under prebiotic conditions, unable to persist beyond **1 billion years even at 0\u00b0C** in aqueous solution (Truong et al., *Icarus*, 2019). This tension between facile synthesis and rapid degradation defines threonine's unique position in origin-of-life chemistry and frames the central challenge: not how to make it, but how to use it before it decomposes.\n\n---\n\n## Five demonstrated routes from simple molecules to threonine\n\nMultiple independent pathways connect simple prebiotic feedstocks (HCN, NH\u2083, H\u2082O, H\u2082S, CH\u2084, UV light) to threonine. Each proceeds through distinct intermediates and operates under different environmental conditions, suggesting that threonine could have formed in diverse early Earth settings.\n\n### Route 1: Strecker synthesis via lactaldehyde (cyanosulfidic pathway)\n\nThe most completely characterized route proceeds through **lactaldehyde** (2-hydroxypropanal) as the key aldehyde precursor. Ritson and Sutherland (*Angewandte Chemie International Edition*, 2013) demonstrated each step experimentally: UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide complexes with H\u2082S as reductant converts HCN to formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde through photoredox cycling. Acetaldehyde reacts with HCN to form acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, which undergoes photoreduction to lactaldehyde at **19% yield** after 2 hours of irradiation. Lactaldehyde then undergoes classic Strecker chemistry \u2014 reaction with NH\u2083 to form an imine, followed by HCN addition to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile (the threonine aminonitrile), which hydrolyzes to threonine and allothreonine as a racemic mixture of diastereomers. The complete pathway requires only HCN, H\u2082O, H\u2082S, Cu minerals, and UV light \u2014 all prebiotically plausible.\n\nPatel et al. (*Nature Chemistry*, 2015) placed this route within the broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism, showing that the threonine aminonitrile is one of four amino acid precursors (alongside those for glycine, alanine, and serine) that arise as \"inevitable by-products\" of the Kiliani\u2013Fischer reductive homologation of HCN that also produces ribonucleotide precursors. A parallel route through glyceraldehyde (rather than lactaldehyde) provides a second entry point: glyceraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN directly yields the threonine aminonitrile.\n\n### Route 2: Miller-Urey spark discharge synthesis\n\nElectric discharge experiments have confirmed threonine production from simple gas mixtures. **Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller** (*Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, 1972) provided the first confirmed detection, using spark discharge on CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O with traces of NH\u2083. Both threonine and allothreonine were identified by ion-exchange chromatography and GC-MS, alongside over 20 other amino acids. The mechanism proceeds through in situ generation of HCN, NH\u2083, and aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) followed by aqueous Strecker synthesis.\n\nReanalysis of Stanley Miller's archived experimental samples revealed additional threonine detections. Parker, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin, and Bada (*PNAS*, 2011) analyzed Miller's unreported 1958 H\u2082S-containing experiment (CH\u2084/NH\u2083/CO\u2082/H\u2082S gas mixture) and detected **23 amino acids including threonine** \u2014 which appeared in the H\u2082S experiment but not in the three other discharge configurations (original, volcanic, silent). The presence of H\u2082S apparently promoted formation of hydroxylated and sulfur-containing amino acids. Johnson et al. (*Science*, 2008) found that Miller's volcanic apparatus (incorporating hot water mist) preferentially synthesized hydroxylated compounds, with **22 amino acids** total. All products were racemic, confirming abiotic origin.\n\n### Route 3: Aldol condensation of glycine and acetaldehyde\n\nThe biological retro-aldol cleavage of threonine (catalyzed by threonine aldolases) yields glycine + acetaldehyde. The reverse \u2014 aldol condensation of glycine with acetaldehyde \u2014 represents a conceptually simple prebiotic route, since both glycine and acetaldehyde rank among the most abundant prebiotic molecules. However, this condensation is **thermodynamically unfavorable** and requires either high glycine concentrations or catalytic assistance to proceed (Fesko, *Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology*, 2016). Both threonine and allothreonine diastereomers form. No purely prebiotic demonstration of this specific aldol condensation has been reported, though the reaction defines the structural relationship between threonine and its simplest precursors.\n\nKoga and Naraoka (*ACS Earth and Space Chemistry*, 2022) demonstrated a related pathway: \u00b9\u00b3C-labeled aldehydes (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde) reacting with ammonia in aqueous solution produced families of **hydroxy amino acids including C\u2083 and C\u2084 structural isomers** that match the distribution found in CM and CR carbonaceous chondrites. This ammonia-aldehyde chemistry provides a route to threonine-related compounds without requiring HCN.\n\n### Route 4: Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids\n\nThe keto acid precursor to threonine is **2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate** (\u03b1-keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate). Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (*Nature*, 2019) demonstrated that Fe\u00b2\u207a promotes reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids at 70\u00b0C, producing glycine, alanine, aspartate, and glutamate from their corresponding keto acids. Kaur et al. (*Chem*, 2024) extended this to H\u2082-driven reductive amination over nickel catalysts at **22\u00b0C and pH 8**. While threonine's specific keto acid precursor was not tested in either study, the principle is established. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Science*, 2006) demonstrated CO-dependent formation of \u03b1-hydroxy and \u03b1-amino acids (including the serine analog, bearing a HOCH\u2082 substituent) at 80\u2013120\u00b0C on Ni-Fe precipitates, suggesting that the threonine homolog (bearing a CH\u2083CHOH substituent) could form via the same chain-elongation mechanism.\n\n### Route 5: Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway\n\nThe Bucherer-Bergs reaction (aldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 \u2192 hydantoin \u2192 amino acid) provides a thermodynamic advantage over direct Strecker synthesis because the hydantoin intermediate acts as a thermodynamic sink. Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (*Nature Chemistry*, 2022) demonstrated this pathway for several \u03b1-keto acids \u2192 amino acids, showing that pyruvate converts to alanine via 5-methylhydantoin and that the chemistry parallels extant biosynthetic pathways. For threonine, lactaldehyde would react with HCN and ammonium carbonate to form 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin, which hydrolyzes to threonine. Hydantoins have been detected in carbonaceous chondrites (Lerner and Cooper, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*, 2005), consistent with this pathway operating in meteorite parent bodies.\n\n---\n\n## Critical intermediates and their roles as branch points\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of threonine intersects with several other biosynthetic pathways through shared intermediates, creating a network rather than a linear sequence.\n\n**Lactaldehyde** (2-hydroxypropanal) is the most direct aldehyde precursor specific to threonine via Strecker chemistry. It forms through UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin at 19% yield (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013). **Glycolaldehyde** serves as the crucial branch point between sugar chemistry and amino acid chemistry \u2014 it enters the formose reaction to produce ribose precursors and simultaneously provides the carbon skeleton for serine (via Strecker) and connects to threonine through further homologation. Its detection in the interstellar medium toward IRAS 16293-2422 and in precometary ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., *PNAS*, 2015) confirms its cosmochemical availability. **Glyceraldehyde** occupies the next node: it is central to Sutherland's ribonucleotide synthesis and directly reacts with HCN and NH\u2083 to form the threonine aminonitrile, making it perhaps the single most important branch point connecting RNA and protein precursor chemistry.\n\n**Acetaldehyde** connects to threonine through two routes \u2014 Strecker synthesis (producing alanine directly, or lactaldehyde via cyanohydrin reduction, then threonine) and aldol condensation with glycine. It is among the simplest and most abundant products of spark discharge experiments and interstellar chemistry. **\u03b1-Ketobutyrate** represents the metabolic connection: in modern biochemistry, threonine dehydratase converts threonine to \u03b1-ketobutyrate, and the reverse (reductive amination) constitutes a plausible prebiotic route. Copley, Smith, and Morowitz (*PNAS*, 2005) proposed that \u03b1-keto acids formed esters with dinucleotides in a proto-metabolic amino acid synthesis, providing selectivity through nucleotide-keto acid interactions. **HCN oligomers** represent a less specific but broad-spectrum source: Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano, and Osuna-Esteban (*Life*, 2013) reviewed 24 experimental conditions and found that **12 of the 20 proteinogenic amino acids**, including threonine, were detected in HCN polymer hydrolysates, with glycine and aspartic acid consistently the most abundant products.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental settings and their suitability for each synthetic step\n\nDifferent prebiotic environments favor different steps in threonine synthesis, and no single setting optimizes the entire pathway. This \"conditions compatibility problem\" is a central challenge.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (Lost City type, 40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311) provide the most favorable thermodynamic conditions for amino acid synthesis. Shock and Canovas (*Science*, 1998) calculated that autotrophic synthesis of all 20 amino acids is exergonic in hot, moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions. White, Bhartia, and Russell (*Earth and Planetary Science Letters*, 2015) demonstrated that mackinawite (FeS) and greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) precipitate in simulated Hadean chimney walls at 40\u201380\u00b0C, with maximum greigite yield at 75\u00b0C. Greigite's Fe\u2084S\u2084 cubane units are structural analogs of active centers in modern hydrogenase and ferredoxin. Lane and Martin (*Journal of Molecular Evolution*, 2012) showed that Fe(Ni)S minerals in alkaline vent micropores could concentrate organics approximately **5,000-fold** via thermophoresis, partially addressing the concentration problem.\n\n**Surface volcanic hot springs and evaporitic pools** favor condensation reactions and UV-driven photochemistry. Damer and Deamer (*Astrobiology*, 2020) proposed that volcanic hot spring pools with wet-dry cycling at 60\u201380\u00b0C drive peptide and RNA-like polymer formation. The cyanosulfidic chemistry of Sutherland operates optimally in surface UV-exposed pools with phosphate buffer at ~35\u00b0C. Lahav, White, and Chang (*Science*, 1978) showed that wet-dry cycling plus temperature cycling in clay environments produces longer oligopeptides in higher yields than temperature fluctuations alone. Campbell et al. (*Nature Communications*, 2019) demonstrated that deliquescent minerals can mediate autonomous wet-dry cycling via humidity changes, achieving **over 10-fold higher oligomerization yields**.\n\n**Black smoker hydrothermal vents** (250\u2013400\u00b0C) are problematic. Bada, Miller, and Zhao (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1995) demonstrated that amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C**. However, the mixing zones where hot fluid encounters cold seawater (100\u2013150\u00b0C) remain viable. Marshall (*Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*, 1994) synthesized amino acids at 200\u2013275\u00b0C from aqueous NH\u2084HCO\u2083 with hydrocarbons, though no synthesis occurred below 150\u00b0C. The synthesis-destruction balance is precarious: Aubrey et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2009) concluded that equilibrium at high temperatures favors net degradation rather than synthesis.\n\n**Ice environments** offer a counterintuitive advantage. Eutectic freezing concentrates solutes in brine channels between ice crystals. Miyakawa et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2002) froze NH\u2084CN solutions for 25 years at -20\u00b0C and -78\u00b0C, producing adenine, guanine, and amino acids \u2014 demonstrating that cold environments can drive prebiotic chemistry while simultaneously protecting labile products from thermal degradation.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts accelerate and direct threonine-relevant reactions\n\nMineral surfaces play three critical roles in prebiotic amino acid chemistry: catalyzing bond formation, concentrating dilute reactants, and potentially inducing chiral selectivity.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** anchor W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Science*, 1998) demonstrated peptide formation from amino acids activated by CO on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces at 100\u00b0C, achieving dipeptide yields of **0.4\u201312.4%** and tripeptide yields of ~0.10%. Their 2006 work (*Science*) showed CO-dependent \u03b1-amino acid synthesis on Ni-Fe precipitates at 80\u2013120\u00b0C using cyano ligands as the C/N source. Pyrite (FeS\u2082) shows particularly interesting photocatalytic properties: a 2024 study in *Nature Communications* demonstrated that natural pyrite produces D-amino acids with enantiomeric excess of **14.5\u201342.4%** via asymmetric photocatalytic reductive amination \u2014 the first demonstration of a mineral surface generating significant chiral bias in amino acid synthesis. Cody, Boctor, and Hazen (*Science*, 2000) showed that carbonylated iron-sulfur compounds produce pyruvate from CO and FeS at hydrothermal conditions, establishing the availability of key \u03b1-keto acid precursors.\n\n**Clay minerals**, particularly montmorillonite, catalyze condensation and polymerization. Ferris et al. (*Nature*, 1996) achieved RNA oligomers up to 50 nucleotides on montmorillonite surfaces. For amino acids, Kitadai et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2015) showed that glycine on montmorillonite at 150\u00b0C for 336 hours converts **~13.9% of monomers** to peptides under dry conditions, with no peptides forming without the mineral. Montmorillonite's interlayer structure provides steric effects that enhance condensation while protecting macromolecules from thermal decomposition. Bujd\u00e1k et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1995) demonstrated hetero-oligomerization (ala-gly-gly from ala + gly\u2082) on Ca-montmorillonite during wet-dry cycling at 80\u00b0C, with approximately 10% oligomer yields after 3 weeks.\n\n**Photocatalytic minerals** offer UV-driven synthesis pathways. ZnS surfaces drive reversible reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids (Wang et al., *Chemical Communications*, 2012), supporting Mulkidjanian's zinc world hypothesis (*Biology Direct*, 2009) that life emerged at photosynthetically active porous ZnS structures. TiO\u2082 has been shown to catalyze amino acid production from simple precursors under near-UV illumination (Dunn, Aikawa, and Bard, *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, 1981). Both minerals could have driven amino acid synthesis in shallow, UV-exposed prebiotic pools.\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic and experimental evidence establishes threonine's abiotic credentials\n\nThe detection of threonine in extraterrestrial materials provides independent confirmation that abiotic synthesis occurs under natural conditions, though contamination complicates interpretation.\n\nThe strongest evidence for indigenous extraterrestrial threonine comes from the **CR2 chondrite GRA 95229** (Graves Nunataks, Antarctica). Pizzarello et al. (*PNAS*, 2012) positively identified threonine and allothreonine alongside other hydroxy amino acids, with the critical observation that **threonine was racemic** \u2014 consistent with abiotic synthesis and ruling out biological contamination. The pristine Antarctic collection conditions and the absence of L-excess make this the most compelling meteoritic detection. In the Murchison meteorite, threonine has been detected at approximately **700 ppb** for L-threonine, but the strong L-enrichment (~99% Lee) is attributed to terrestrial contamination (Kato et al., *Scientific Reports*, 2017; Glavin et al., *Meteoritics and Planetary Science*, 2020). Similarly, Tagish Lake analyses showed ~99% Lee for threonine (Glavin et al., 2012), again flagged as contamination. Only **12 of the 20 proteinogenic amino acids** have been confirmed in meteorites with indigenous signatures.\n\nInterstellar ice analog experiments provide complementary evidence. Nuevo et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2008) tentatively detected threonine in organic residues from vacuum UV irradiation of ice mixtures (H\u2082O, CO, CO\u2082, CH\u2083OH, CH\u2084, NH\u2083) at 10\u201380 K \u2014 the first such detection in ice photolysis experiments. Separately, UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene + H\u2082O + NH\u2083 ice at 15 K produced 13 amino acids including threonine (Nuevo et al., *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*, 2008). These experiments demonstrate that threonine can form through non-aqueous photochemistry in interstellar environments.\n\nQuantitative yields from laboratory experiments remain low. In spark discharge experiments, threonine appears at trace levels relative to glycine (the dominant product). Weber (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1998) achieved 0.08% homoserine (threonine's biosynthetic precursor) from formaldehyde + glycolaldehyde + NH\u2084Cl with thiol catalyst at 40\u00b0C over 35 days. The cyanosulfidic pathway achieves 19% yield for the lactaldehyde intermediate, but overall threonine yields through the complete Strecker sequence remain unquantified in the published literature.\n\n---\n\n## Stereochemistry creates a fourfold selectivity challenge\n\nThreonine's two chiral centers (C2 and C3) generate four stereoisomers \u2014 L-threonine (2S,3R), D-threonine (2R,3S), L-allothreonine (2S,3S), and D-allothreonine (2R,3R) \u2014 creating challenges beyond those faced by amino acids with a single stereocenter. Abiotic Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde produces roughly equal amounts of threonine and allothreonine diastereomers, each as a racemic D/L mixture, yielding approximately 25% of the biologically relevant L-threonine. Schroeder and Bada (*Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*, 1977) studied threonine epimerization kinetics in fossil foraminifera and showed that L-threonine epimerizes to D-allothreonine at the \u03b1-carbon faster than \u03b2-carbon racemization, meaning the diastereomer ratio shifts more rapidly than the enantiomeric ratio.\n\nPotential mechanisms for generating enantiomeric excess include **circularly polarized light (CPL)** from star-forming regions, which can induce 1\u20132% ee in amino acids through preferential photodestruction (Modica et al., *Astrophysical Journal*, 2014). This small seed can be amplified: Breslow demonstrated that as little as **1% Lee can reach 95:5 L:D ratio** through simple evaporation, exploiting differential solubility of racemic versus enantiopure crystals. Pyrite's asymmetric photocatalysis (14.5\u201342.4% ee for D-amino acids) represents a mineral-based alternative. However, for threonine specifically, aqueous alteration on meteorite parent bodies promotes racemization of amino acids with \u03b1-hydrogen atoms, meaning any original ee would erode over geological timescales.\n\n---\n\n## Stability, concentration, and the fundamental bottlenecks\n\nThreonine faces several interrelated challenges that constrain its prebiotic accumulation and utilization.\n\n**Thermal instability** is the most severe constraint. Threonine's \u03b2-hydroxyl group enables rapid \u03b2-elimination yielding dehydroaminobutyric acid, analogous to serine's well-characterized decomposition. K\u00f6rner (*ChemSusChem*, 2021) noted that **no systematic investigation of threonine decomposition products under hydrothermal conditions had been performed** as of that date \u2014 a remarkable gap. What is known places threonine among the most labile proteinogenic amino acids: in dry heating studies (80\u2013180\u00b0C), it ranks below most nonpolar and acidic amino acids in stability. Truong et al. (*Icarus*, 2019) established that threonine and aspartic acid cannot persist beyond 1 billion years at 273 K, making them the least durable proteinogenic amino acids \u2014 critical for both origin-of-life scenarios and biosignature detection on icy ocean worlds like Europa and Enceladus.\n\nThe **concentration problem** applies broadly to prebiotic amino acids but affects threonine acutely given its instability. At estimated prebiotic ocean concentrations of ~10\u207b\u2074 M glycine, Ba\u00fa et al. calculated that \"tens of thousands of terrestrial prebiotic oceans would not have sufficed to obtain a single Gly\u2089 molecule at equilibrium.\" Solutions include mineral surface adsorption (layered double hydroxides can concentrate, align, and template amino acids per Erastova et al., *Nature Communications*, 2017), eutectic freezing in ice channels, evaporitic pool concentration via wet-dry cycling, thermophoretic concentration in hydrothermal micropores (~5,000-fold per Lane and Martin), and aerosol chemistry at air-water interfaces.\n\nThe **selectivity problem** \u2014 producing threonine specifically rather than complex mixtures \u2014 remains largely unsolved. The cyanosulfidic pathway offers the most promising selectivity through its constrained reaction network, but still produces mixtures. Islam, Bu\u010dar, and Powner (*Nature Chemistry*, 2017) demonstrated that 2-aminothiazole selectively sequesters glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from complex mixtures, potentially providing a physicochemical selection mechanism. The **water problem** (condensation reactions disfavored in aqueous solution, with \u0394G \u2248 +3.5 kcal/mol for glycine dimerization) applies to subsequent peptide incorporation. Proposed solutions include wet-dry cycling, depsipeptide intermediates (ester bonds formed first, then converted to amides), thioester chemistry, and aminonitrile coupling in water (Canavelli, Islam, and Powner, *Nature*, 2019).\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThreonine's prebiotic synthesis is better understood than for most proteinogenic amino acids, primarily thanks to the cyanosulfidic framework that connects its formation to the same chemistry producing RNA precursors. The Ritson-Sutherland pathway through lactaldehyde provides a complete, experimentally validated route from HCN to the threonine aminonitrile using only prebiotically available materials. Spark discharge experiments confirm that electrical energy acting on simple gas mixtures \u2014 particularly those containing H\u2082S \u2014 produces threonine alongside dozens of other amino acids. Racemic threonine in the pristine CR2 meteorite GRA 95229 demonstrates that abiotic synthesis occurs naturally in asteroid parent bodies.\n\nThree critical gaps remain. First, threonine's thermal and hydrolytic instability means it must be synthesized and utilized on timescales shorter than its decomposition half-life \u2014 a constraint that strongly favors lower-temperature environments (alkaline vents, surface pools, ice) over high-temperature hydrothermal settings. Second, the systematic study of threonine decomposition products under prebiotic conditions has never been performed, leaving the kinetics and products of its degradation poorly constrained. Third, achieving the stereochemical selectivity needed to produce predominantly L-threonine (one of four stereoisomers) from racemic abiotic synthesis remains an open problem, though pyrite's asymmetric photocatalysis and CPL-seeded amplification mechanisms offer partial solutions. The convergence of cyanosulfidic chemistry, meteorite analysis, and mineral catalysis research is steadily narrowing these gaps, positioning threonine as a tractable case study for understanding how biological amino acids emerged from prebiotic chemistry.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.93,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.95,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n      \"target_