ermal formaldehyde generation of P3 with the lactaldehyde Strecker route of P1. Same concerns about rxn_002. However, once formaldehyde is produced, the downstream cyanohydrin \u2192 photoreduction \u2192 Strecker sequence is well-validated. The environmental transition from hydrothermal (CO2 reduction) to surface (UV photochemistry) is geologically plausible \u2014 hydrothermal effluent reaching shallow UV-exposed pools.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Consider shortening by using cyanosulfidic formaldehyde generation instead of hydrothermal\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.50\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.62,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.55,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.62,\n      \"feedback\": \"The aldol condensation of glycine and acetaldehyde (rxn_011) is the biological retro-aldol reaction run in reverse. The literature explicitly states this is thermodynamically unfavorable and that 'no purely prebiotic demonstration of this specific aldol condensation has been reported' (Fesko 2016). Without catalytic assistance or extreme concentrations, this route is not viable under prebiotic conditions. The glycine and acetaldehyde generation steps are excellent, but the final step fails.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Add a mineral catalyst (e.g., layered double hydroxide, or zinc-containing mineral)\", \"Consider whether depsipeptide-type activation or thioester coupling could make this step more feasible\", \"Alternatively, reclassify this as a minor/low-yield route\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.86,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"The Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route is well-supported by Pulletikurti et al. 2022 and by the detection of hydantoins in carbonaceous chondrites (Lerner & Cooper 2005). The hydantoin acts as a thermodynamic sink, making this route potentially more favorable than direct Strecker in dilute solutions. The lactaldehyde generation is the same well-validated cyanosulfidic sequence. Hydantoin hydrolysis (rxn_014) requires sustained aqueous conditions at moderate temperature. Minor concern: the Bucherer-Bergs reaction for this specific substrate (lactaldehyde) has not been explicitly demonstrated.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Note that hydantoin stability provides a reservoir effect, potentially helping with the concentration problem\", \"Specify hydrolysis conditions for rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.72\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n      \"feedback\": \"The iron-sulfur world keto acid route is conceptually sound and supported by Cody et al. 2000 (pyruvate from CO/FeS), Muchowska et al. 2019 (reductive amination of keto acids), and Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 2006 (chain elongation). However, the specific chain elongation of pyruvate with formaldehyde to alpha-keto-beta-hydroxybutyrate (rxn_016) is speculative \u2014 the aldol between an alpha-keto acid and formaldehyde is plausible but undemonstrated. The reductive amination (rxn_017) also has not been tested with this specific hydroxylated substrate. All three steps are hydrothermal, missing the environmental flow requirement. The literature cautions that threonine is unstable at hydrothermal temperatures.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Add experimental evidence or more specific conditions for the pyruvate + formaldehyde aldol\", \"Address threonine thermal instability at hydrothermal temperatures (Bada et al. 1995)\", \"Consider routing the final product through a cooler downstream environment\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.60\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.65,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.65,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.55,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.63,\n      \"feedback\": \"HCN oligomerization is well-established (rxn_018), and amino acid release from HCN polymer hydrolysis is documented (Ruiz-Bermejo et al. 2013: 12 of 20 proteinogenic amino acids). However, threonine yields from HCN polymers are very low and inconsistent across studies. The pathway is too non-specific \u2014 it is essentially a black box where complex polymers release trace amino acids. The two-step nature means no mechanistic control. Miyakawa et al. 2002 showed amino acids from frozen NH4CN, but threonine was not highlighted as a major product.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Acknowledge low and variable yields for threonine specifically\", \"Consider this a supplementary background source rather than a primary pathway\", \"Specify polymer hydrolysis conditions more precisely\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_0