s stated.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_020\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Decompose rxn_020 into mechanistically explicit steps\", \"Specify what mineral or energy source drives the reaction\", \"Cite Koga & Naraoka 2022 explicitly and note the mixture of structural isomers produced\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-constructed and literature-grounded synthesis network for threonine. The core strength lies in the cyanosulfidic pathways (P1, P2, P6), which directly map onto the experimentally validated work of Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). The network topology is excellent: 21 molecules and 20 reactions create a dense bipartite graph with 5 well-chosen hub molecules (HCN, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, threonine aminonitrile) that provide genuine redundancy. Multiple convergent routes reach threonine through chemically distinct intermediates. The environmental interconnection is generally well-handled, with hydrothermal CO2 reduction feeding surface photoredox chemistry feeding biochemical-stage hydrolysis. Mineral agents are specified for hydrothermal reactions (greigite, magnetite, iron-sulfide). Key concerns: (1) rxn_002 (formate \u2192 formaldehyde) needs stronger support; (2) the iron-sulfur keto acid route (P7, P9) involves undemonstrated specific reactions and ignores threonine's thermal instability at hydrothermal temperatures; (3) P5 (glycine + acetaldehyde aldol) is thermodynamically unfavorable without catalysis; (4) P8 and P10 are too non-specific. The network would benefit from addressing threonine's well-documented thermal lability (Truong et al. 2019) and the diastereomer problem (all routes produce threonine + allothreonine mixtures). Five of ten pathways achieve approval (P1, P2, P3, P4, P6), which is sufficient for a robust network.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.92,\n  