s not solve the fundamental feasibility questions. Additionally, all steps remain hydrothermal, creating the instability problem for threonine at elevated temperatures.', 'The ammonia-aldehyde route (rxn_020) is inspired by Koga & Naraoka 2022, who showed hydroxy amino acid formation from aldehydes + NH3. However, the mechanism is poorly defined \u2014 a direct three-component reaction producing a specific amino acid from glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde + NH3 requires multiple steps (aldol, amination, oxidation/reduction) that are conflated into a single reaction node. The literature describes C3-C4 hydroxy amino acid structural isomers, not necessarily threonine specifically. This pathway is too vague to be chemically credible as stated.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network generates threonine through 10 distinct pathways grounded in the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic framework (Ritson & Sutherland 2013, Patel et al. 2015), Miller-Urey spark discharge chemistry (Parker et al. 2011), and the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway (Pulletikurti et al. 2022). The network is anchored by three formaldehyde-producing entry points: (1) HCN photoredox on Cu minerals at the surface, (2) Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite in hydrothermal vents, and (3) hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate followed by further reduction on native iron. Formaldehyde is the primary hub, feeding into glycolaldehyde, which branches to either acetaldehyde (en route to lactaldehyde via cyanohydrin photoreduction) or glyceraldehyde. Both lactaldehyde and glyceraldehyde undergo Strecker synthesis to yield threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine. An alternative Bucherer-Bergs route through a hydantoin intermediate provides a thermodynamic sink pathway. A tenth pathway ent