     \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-2(7)3(5)4-6/h2-3,7H,5H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2O3/c1-2(8)3-4(9)7-5(10)6-3/h2-3,8H,1H3,(H2,6,7,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is adsorbed on the Fe4S4 cubane surface of greigite, which is structurally analogous to biological ferredoxin [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 to formate via a surface-bound formylate intermediate. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing, alkaline conditions of Lost City-type vents.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite (Fe3S4) precipitates in simulated Hadean alkaline vent chimney walls with maximum yield at 75\u00b0C (White, Bhartia & Russell, Earth and Planetary Science Letters, 2015). Its Fe4S4 cubane units are structural analogs of [Fe4S4] clusters in modern hydrogenase and ferredoxin. CO2 hydrogenation to formate on iron-sulfur minerals under hydrothermal conditions is well-established (Shock & Canovas, Science, 1998 showed amino acid synthesis from CO2 is exergonic under these conditions). Lane & Martin (Journal of Molecular Evolution, 2012) showed Fe(Ni)S minerals in alkaline vent micropores concentrate organics ~5,000-fold via thermophoresis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Sub-seafloor hydrothermal conditions; CO2 + H2 from serpentinization; formaldehyde is a primary C1 product of FTT synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces proceeds through CO2 hydrogenation via surface-bound CO intermediate, which is further reduced to formaldehyde. Magnetite provides the catalytic iron oxide surface. At 400-500K under high H2 partial pressures, the reaction yields a distribution of oxygenated C1-C3 products including formaldehyde, methanol, and formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite at hydrothermal conditions produces formaldehyde among other oxygenated organics. McCollom & Seewald (Chemical Reviews, 2007) reviewed extensive evidence for FTT synthesis under hydrothermal conditions. This provides a hydrothermal entry point for formaldehyde that feeds into surface chemistry. The formaldehyde produced would be transported to cooler surface environments via hydrothermal fluid circulation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox synthesis of formaldehyde from HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I) cyanide complexes\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide complexes\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), phosphate buffer pH ~7, H2S as sacrificial reductant; anaerobic surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN forms Cu(I) cyanide complexes in solution. UV irradiation drives single-electron photoredox cycling: Cu(I)\u2192Cu(II) + e\u207b, with H2S providing the reducing equivalents to regenerate Cu(I). HCN is sequentially photoreduced through formiminyl radical intermediates to formaldehyde (HCHO). The mechanism proceeds via HCN \u2192 formaldehyde imine \u2192 formaldehyde upon hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 2013) demonstrated experimentally that UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide complexes with H2S as reductant converts HCN to formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde through photoredox cycling. This is the entry point to the cyanosulfidic network that produces all amino acid and nucleotide precursors. Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) placed this within the broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)2 or borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline conditions pH 10-12 favor formose initiation; borate stabilizes glycolaldehyde against further oligomerization; equivalent to first step of formose reaction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under alkaline conditions, formaldehyde undergoes base-catalyzed aldol self-condensation: the enolate of one formaldehyde molecule attacks the carbonyl of a second, yielding glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO). Borate complexation of the 1,2-diol product stabilizes glycolaldehyde against further condensation (preventing tar formation), channeling the formose reaction toward C2 products. This is the rate-limiting initiation step of the formose reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction (n HCHO \u2192 sugars) is well-established with Ca(OH)2 catalysis (Breslow, Tetrahedron Letters, 1959). Borate minerals stabilize glycolaldehyde and ribose against degradation. Ricardo et al. (Science, 2004) showed borate complexation selectively stabilizes specific sugar products. Glycolaldehyde is detected in interstellar medium toward IRAS 16293-2422 and in precometary ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., PNAS, 2015), confirming its cosmochemical prevalence. In the cyanosulfidic framework, glycolaldehyde also forms directly from HCN photoredox (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolaldehyde to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I) cyanide complexes\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide complexes\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), H2S as reductant, phosphate buffer\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) undergoes UV-driven photoreduction in the Cu(I)/H2S system. The hydroxyl group at C1 is reduced: the C-OH bond is reductively cleaved, replacing OH with H to yield acetaldehyde (CH3CHO). This is a Kiliani\u2013Fischer-type reductive deoxygenation driven by the same Cu photoredox cycle that generates formaldehyde from HCN.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 2013) demonstrated that the Cu(I)/H2S/UV system reduces glycolaldehyde to acetaldehyde as part of the reductive homologation series. Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) showed this reaction is integral to the cyanosulfidic network, linking sugar chemistry to amino acid precursor synthesis. Acetaldehyde is a critical branch point: it leads to alanine (directly via Strecker) or to threonine (via cyanohydrin \u2192 lactaldehyde).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mild base (phosphate buffer)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9 favors cyanohydrin formation; rapid equilibrium reaction; nucleophilic CN\u207b attacks electrophilic carbonyl\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under mildly basic conditions, HCN deprotonates to form cyanide ion (CN\u207b), which acts as a nucleophile attacking the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde. The resulting alkoxide is protonated to yield acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile, 2-hydroxypropanenitrile, CH3CH(OH)CN). This is a well-characterized, rapid equilibrium reaction that drives toward product at pH 7-9.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin formation is a standard and rapid reaction well-known in prebiotic chemistry. Ritson & Sutherland (Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 2013) used this reaction as an intermediate step: acetaldehyde cyanohydrin is the direct precursor to lactaldehyde via photoreduction. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds spontaneously in aqueous HCN solutions containing aldehydes. Phosphate buffer maintains optimal pH (Patel et al., Nature Chemistry, 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I) cyanide complexes\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide complexes\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), H2S as reductant, 2 hours irradiation achieves 19% yield; produces racemic lactaldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (C\u2261N) of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (CH3CH(OH)CN) is photoreduced to an aldehyde via the Cu(I)/H2S/UV system. The cyanide carbon is reduced: C\u2261N \u2192 CH=NH (imine) \u2192 CHO (aldehyde upon hydrolysis), yielding lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal, CH3CH(OH)CHO). This is the same photoredox mechanism as rxn_003 and rxn_005 but applied to a nitrile substrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 2013) demonstrated this specific reaction experimentally, achieving 19% yield of lactaldehyde after 2 hours UV irradiation. This is the key step that generates the threonine-specific aldehyde precursor from the more general cyanosulfidic network. Lactaldehyde is the most direct aldehyde precursor to threonine via Strecker synthesis. The yield of 19% is notable for a prebiotically plausible photochemical reaction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals, Ca(OH)2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline conditions; borate stabilizes the glyceraldehyde product through cis-diol complexation; second step of formose-type homologation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base-catalyzed aldol condensation: glycolaldehyde enolizes under alkaline conditions, and the resulting enolate attacks formaldehyde at its carbonyl carbon. The aldol product is glyceraldehyde (HOCH2CH(OH)CHO). Borate minerals complex the 1,2-diol moiety of glyceraldehyde, stabilizing it against retro-aldol cleavage and further condensation. This is the second step of Kiliani\u2013Fischer homologation in the formose pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyceraldehyde is central to Sutherland's ribonucleotide synthesis and simultaneously connects to threonine via Strecker chemistry (Patel et al., Nature Chemistry, 2015). Borate stabilization of glyceraldehyde is supported by Ricardo et al. (Science, 2004). The aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde is a well-established formose reaction step. Islam, Bu\u010dar & Powner (Nature Chemistry, 2017) showed that 2-aminothiazole can selectively sequester glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from complex mixtures.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9; sequential imine formation then CN\u207b addition; produces racemic mixture of threonine aminonitrile and allothreonine aminonitrile diastereomers (~1:1 ratio)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis in two steps: (1) lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form an imine (CH3CH(OH)CH=NH) with loss of water; (2) cyanide ion (from HCN) attacks the electrophilic imine carbon to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile (threonine aminonitrile). The reaction proceeds through a Schiff base intermediate. Both threonine and allothreonine diastereomeric aminonitriles form in approximately equal amounts because the C3 stereocenter of lactaldehyde is not selectively controlled, and the new C2 stereocenter forms without stereoselection.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) demonstrated that the threonine aminonitrile is one of four amino acid precursors (alongside glycine, alanine, and serine precursors) that arise as 'inevitable by-products' of the cyanosulfidic network. The Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde is the most direct and experimentally validated route to the threonine carbon skeleton. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) established the complete pathway from HCN to lactaldehyde; the subsequent Strecker step is classical aqueous-phase chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9; glyceraldehyde undergoes Strecker at C1 aldehyde; produces threonine aminonitrile and allothreonine aminonitrile as racemic diastereomeric mixture\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde (HOCH2CH(OH)CHO) reacts with NH3 to form an imine at C1, followed by HCN addition to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile. Note: this reaction involves formal reduction and loss of the terminal hydroxymethyl group, or alternatively proceeds through a rearrangement. In the Patel et al. framework, glyceraldehyde serves as an alternative aldehyde entry point that directly generates the threonine aminonitrile scaffold, connecting sugar and amino acid chemistry through a shared C3 intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) explicitly identified glyceraldehyde as a parallel entry point: 'glyceraldehyde (rather than lactaldehyde) provides a second entry point: glyceraldehyde + NH3 + HCN directly yields the threonine aminonitrile.' This convergence is significant because glyceraldehyde is also the key intermediate in ribonucleotide synthesis, meaning amino acid and RNA precursor chemistry share the same starting materials. This represents the deepest connection between the two polymer systems.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mild aqueous conditions; nitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide intermediate; pH 4-7 accelerates hydrolysis; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine mixture. Must occur at low temperature to prevent thermal decomposition of product (Truong et al. 2019 showed threonine is among least stable amino acids).\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis proceeds in two steps: (1) nucleophilic addition of water to the C\u2261N bond yields an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide); (2) further hydrolysis cleaves the C-N(amide) bond to yield the free carboxylic acid (threonine) and ammonia. Under mildly acidic conditions (pH 4-7), both steps proceed at moderate rates at 300-340K without catalysts.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the final step of the Strecker synthesis and proceeds spontaneously in aqueous solution. This is the terminal reaction in the cyanosulfidic pathway to threonine. Importantly, this step must occur at relatively low temperatures: Truong et al. (Icarus, 2019) established that threonine cannot persist beyond 1 billion years even at 0\u00b0C due to its labile \u03b2-hydroxyl group enabling rapid \u03b2-elimination. This thermal instability strongly constrains the final steps to low-temperature environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ammonium carbonate (from NH3 + CO2)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-10; (NH4)2CO3 provides both NH3 and CO2 sources; hydantoin forms as thermodynamic sink product, more stable than aminonitrile; wet-dry cycling may concentrate reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The Bucherer-Bergs reaction proceeds via: (1) lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin (lactaldehyde cyanohydrin); (2) cyanohydrin + NH3 \u2192 aminonitrile; (3) aminonitrile + CO2 \u2192 carbamoylamino nitrile; (4) intramolecular cyclization \u2192 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin. The hydantoin ring is a thermodynamic sink, making the overall reaction more favorable than stopping at the aminonitrile stage. Ammonium carbonate serves as the source of both NH3 and CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (Nature Chemistry, 2022) demonstrated the Bucherer-Bergs pathway for amino acid synthesis, showing that \u03b1-keto acids convert to amino acids via hydantoin intermediates and that the chemistry parallels extant biosynthetic pathways. For threonine, lactaldehyde would form 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin. Hydantoins have been detected in carbonaceous chondrites (Lerner & Cooper, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta, 2005), providing extraterrestrial evidence for this pathway operating on meteorite parent bodies.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydantoin hydrolysis to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-10; hydantoin ring opens via hydrolysis at both C=O positions; may require moderate heating or prolonged contact with water; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydantoin hydrolysis proceeds through sequential ring-opening: first hydrolysis at C4 yields N-carbamoyl-threonine (ring-opened intermediate), then decarboxylation and hydrolysis of the remaining urea linkage yields free threonine + CO2 + NH3. The reaction is driven by the thermodynamic stability of the amino acid product relative to the hydantoin under aqueous conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2022) demonstrated that hydantoin hydrolysis to amino acids proceeds under mild prebiotic conditions, completing the Bucherer-Bergs pathway. The hydantoin serves as a protected, stable form of the amino acid that can accumulate and subsequently release threonine upon hydrolysis. This pathway provides an alternative to direct Strecker synthesis that avoids the thermodynamically less favorable aminonitrile intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe0) and iron-nickel alloys\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Strongly reducing conditions; Fe0 serves as both catalyst and reductant; formate is the initial CO2 reduction product that undergoes further reduction to formaldehyde; product must be rapidly transported to cooler zones to prevent over-reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate (HCOO\u207b) adsorbs on native iron surfaces. Fe0 serves as a two-electron donor, reducing formate through a surface-bound formyl intermediate (HCO*) to formaldehyde (HCHO). The reaction is thermodynamically driven by the oxidation of Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+ (highly exergonic). On mackinawite surfaces, H2 can also provide reducing equivalents via heterolytic splitting. The formaldehyde product must be rapidly removed from the hot zone to avoid further reduction to methanol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (Nature Ecology & Evolution, 2020) demonstrated that native metals (Fe, Ni, and Fe-Ni alloys) catalyze CO2 fixation to formate and further reduced C1 species under simulated hydrothermal conditions. The stepwise reduction CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 methanol follows decreasing oxidation state and is thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing conditions (low fO2) of Hadean hydrothermal systems. Herschy et al. (Journal of Molecular Evolution, 2014) showed similar chemistry in alkaline vent simulations. This reaction connects hydrothermal CO2 fixation (rxn_001) to the formaldehyde hub that feeds surface cyanosulfidic chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Miller-Urey spark discharge synthesis of acetaldehyde and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"electrical discharge (lightning)\", \"volcanic aerosols\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K (post-discharge aqueous phase)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrical discharge provides activation energy; H2S enhances hydroxylated product yields\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing atmosphere (CH4/NH3/H2O/H2S); spark discharge generates radical species and reactive intermediates in gas phase; products dissolve in aqueous surface pools; H2S atmosphere specifically promotes threonine-relevant hydroxylated intermediates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge through a CH4/NH3/H2O/H2S gas mixture generates reactive radical species (CH3\u2022, CN\u2022, NH2\u2022, OH\u2022, HS\u2022). Radical recombination and subsequent reactions produce HCN, aldehydes (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), and other reactive intermediates. These dissolve in the aqueous phase where Strecker synthesis occurs spontaneously. H2S promotes formation of hydroxylated species through thiol-mediated radical chemistry. The process is a one-pot generation of the key feedstocks (HCN, acetaldehyde) for subsequent threonine synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Parker, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin & Bada (PNAS, 2011) analyzed Miller's unreported 1958 H2S-containing spark discharge experiment (CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S) and detected 23 amino acids including threonine \u2014 which appeared in the H2S experiment but not in other configurations. The H2S atmosphere specifically promoted hydroxylated amino acid production. Johnson et al. (Science, 2008) found Miller's volcanic apparatus produced 22 amino acids including hydroxylated species. Ring, Wolman, Friedmann & Miller (PNAS, 1972) first confirmed threonine and allothreonine detection in spark discharge products. The mechanism proceeds via in situ Strecker synthesis of the dissolved discharge products.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cyanosulfidic pathway via acetaldehyde-lactaldehyde-Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"The primary experimentally validated route from Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). HCN is photoreduced to formaldehyde via Cu(I)/H2S/UV, dimerized to glycolaldehyde, photoreduced to acetaldehyde, converted to cyanohydrin by HCN, photoreduced to lactaldehyde (19% yield), then Strecker synthesis with NH3/HCN yields threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine. All surface-environment UV photochemistry until final hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic pathway via glyceraldehyde branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative cyanosulfidic route where glycolaldehyde undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to yield glyceraldehyde instead of photoreduction to acetaldehyde. Glyceraldehyde + NH3 + HCN directly yields threonine aminonitrile, connecting sugar and amino acid chemistry. This branch point is critical as glyceraldehyde is also the entry to Sutherland's ribonucleotide synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde \u2192 cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde-Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde is produced by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite under hydrothermal conditions (400-500K), transported to surface via hydrothermal fluid circulation, then enters the cyanosulfidic pathway at the glycolaldehyde synthesis step. Demonstrates Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical environmental flow.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde \u2192 cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde-Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Two-step hydrothermal carbon fixation: CO2 is first reduced to formate on greigite, then formate is further reduced to formaldehyde on native iron. Formaldehyde enters the surface cyanosulfidic pathway. This is the longest pathway, demonstrating full Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical environmental chain.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route\",\n      \"description\": \"Follows the cyanosulfidic pathway to lactaldehyde (as in P1), but diverges at lactaldehyde into the Bucherer-Bergs reaction with HCN + NH3 + CO2 to form a hydantoin thermodynamic sink intermediate, which then hydrolyzes to threonine. The hydantoin intermediate is more stable than the aminonitrile, providing a reservoir for threonine accumulation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde feeds into the glyceraldehyde branch: formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine. Combines hydrothermal carbon fixation with the sugar-amino acid crossover point at glyceraldehyde.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Full hydrothermal CO2 fixation chain (CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde) feeding into the glyceraldehyde Strecker route. The longest glyceraldehyde-based pathway, demonstrating maximum environmental interconnection.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde enters the cyanosulfidic pathway and is channeled through the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route rather than direct Strecker aminonitrile hydrolysis. Combines hydrothermal entry with the thermodynamically favored hydantoin pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Full hydrothermal chain \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs route\",\n      \"description\": \"Maximum-length pathway from CO2 through two hydrothermal reduction steps, into surface cyanosulfidic chemistry, through the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin branch. Demonstrates the most complete environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal CO2 fixation \u2192 Hydrothermal formate reduction \u2192 Surface photochemistry \u2192 Biochemical hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Miller-Urey spark discharge \u2192 lactaldehyde-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark discharge on CH4/NH3/H2O/H2S atmosphere generates acetaldehyde and HCN directly (Parker et al. 2011). Acetaldehyde enters the cyanohydrin \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine pathway. This bypasses the formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde cyanosulfidic chain, providing an independent atmospheric entry to the acetaldehyde hub. H2S atmosphere specifically enhances hydroxylated amino acid yields.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde \u2014 primary C1 hub receiving input from three independent sources (cyanosulfidic photoredox, hydrothermal FTT, hydrothermal formate reduction) and feeding all downstream pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycolaldehyde \u2014 C2 branch point where formose/aldol chemistry diverges to either acetaldehyde (cyanosulfidic photoreduction, leading to lactaldehyde route) or glyceraldehyde (aldol with formaldehyde, connecting sugar and amino acid chemistry)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde \u2014 C2 hub receiving input from both cyanosulfidic photoreduction and Miller-Urey spark discharge, feeding exclusively into the cyanohydrin \u2192 lactaldehyde branch\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde \u2014 threonine-specific C3 aldehyde hub and the key divergence point between Strecker synthesis (\u2192 aminonitrile \u2192 threonine) and Bucherer-Bergs (\u2192 hydantoin \u2192 threonine). 19% yield from cyanohydrin photoreduction is the rate-limiting step.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Threonine aminonitrile \u2014 penultimate intermediate receiving convergent input from two Strecker routes (lactaldehyde-based and glyceraldehyde-based), feeding into final hydrolysis. This is the key convergence where the two cyanosulfidic branches (acetaldehyde\u2192lactaldehyde vs. formaldehyde\u2192glyceraldehyde) reunite.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "This network generates threonine through 10 distinct pathways grounded in the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic framework (Ritson & Sutherland 2013, Patel et al. 2015), Miller-Urey spark discharge chemistry (Parker et al. 2011), and the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway (Pulletikurti et al. 2022). The network is anchored by three formaldehyde-producing entry points: (1) HCN photoredox on Cu minerals at the surface, (2) Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite in hydrothermal vents, and (3) hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate followed by further reduction on native iron. Formaldehyde is the primary hub, feeding into glycolaldehyde, which branches to either acetaldehyde (en route to lactaldehyde via cyanohydrin photoreduction) or glyceraldehyde. Both lactaldehyde and glyceraldehyde undergo Strecker synthesis to yield threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine. An alternative Bucherer-Bergs route through a hydantoin intermediate provides a thermodynamic sink pathway. A tenth pathway enters via spark discharge production of acetaldehyde. All abiotic routes produce racemic threonine/allothreonine diastereomer mixtures (~25% L-threonine). Threonine's documented thermal instability (half-life <1 Gyr at 0\u00b0C; Truong et al. 2019) constrains the network to low-temperature surface and biochemical environments for final steps.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H5NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanenitrile", "common_name": "acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H5NO/c1-2(5)3-4/h2,5H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(5)3-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-2(7)3(5)4-6/h2-3,7H,5H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2O3/c1-2(8)3-4(9)7-5(10)6-3/h2-3,8H,1H3,(H2,6,7,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is adsorbed on the Fe4S4 cubane surface of greigite, which is structurally analogous to biological ferredoxin [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 to formate via a surface-bound formylate intermediate. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing, alkaline conditions of Lost City-type vents.", "reasoning": "Greigite (Fe3S4) precipitates in simulated Hadean alkaline vent chimney walls with maximum yield at 75\u00b0C (White, Bhartia & Russell, Earth and Planetary Science Letters, 2015). Its Fe4S4 cubane units are structural analogs of [Fe4S4] clusters in modern hydrogenase and ferredoxin. CO2 hydrogenation to formate on iron-sulfur minerals under hydrothermal conditions is well-established (Shock & Canovas, Science, 1998 showed amino acid synthesis from CO2 is exergonic under these conditions). Lane & Martin (Journal of Molecular Evolution, 2012) showed Fe(Ni)S minerals in alkaline vent micropores concentrate organics ~5,000-fold via thermophoresis."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Sub-seafloor hydrothermal conditions; CO2 + H2 from serpentinization; formaldehyde is a primary C1 product of FTT synthesis"}, "mechanism": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces proceeds through CO2 hydrogenation via surface-bound CO intermediate, which is further reduced to formaldehyde. Magnetite provides the catalytic iron oxide surface. At 400-500K under high H2 partial pressures, the reaction yields a distribution of oxygenated C1-C3 products including formaldehyde, methanol, and formate.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite at hydrothermal conditions produces formaldehyde among other oxygenated organics. McCollom & Seewald (Chemical Reviews, 2007) reviewed extensive evidence for FTT synthesis under hydrothermal conditions. This provides a hydrothermal entry point for formaldehyde that feeds into surface chemistry. The formaldehyde produced would be transported to cooler surface environments via hydrothermal fluid circulation."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox synthesis of formaldehyde from HCN", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I) cyanide complexes", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide complexes", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (254 nm), phosphate buffer pH ~7, H2S as sacrificial reductant; anaerobic surface pool"}, "mechanism": "HCN forms Cu(I) cyanide complexes in solution. UV irradiation drives single-electron photoredox cycling: Cu(I)\u2192Cu(II) + e\u207b, with H2S providing the reducing equivalents to regenerate Cu(I). HCN is sequentially photoreduced through formiminyl radical intermediates to formaldehyde (HCHO). The mechanism proceeds via HCN \u2192 formaldehyde imine \u2192 formaldehyde upon hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 2013) demonstrated experimentally that UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide complexes with H2S as reductant converts HCN to formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde through photoredox cycling. This is the entry point to the cyanosulfidic network that produces all amino acid and nucleotide precursors. Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) placed this within the broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)2 or borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline conditions pH 10-12 favor formose initiation; borate stabilizes glycolaldehyde against further oligomerization; equivalent to first step of formose reaction"}, "mechanism": "Under alkaline conditions, formaldehyde undergoes base-catalyzed aldol self-condensation: the enolate of one formaldehyde molecule attacks the carbonyl of a second, yielding glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO). Borate complexation of the 1,2-diol product stabilizes glycolaldehyde against further condensation (preventing tar formation), channeling the formose reaction toward C2 products. This is the rate-limiting initiation step of the formose reaction.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction (n HCHO \u2192 sugars) is well-established with Ca(OH)2 catalysis (Breslow, Tetrahedron Letters, 1959). Borate minerals stabilize glycolaldehyde and ribose against degradation. Ricardo et al. (Science, 2004) showed borate complexation selectively stabilizes specific sugar products. Glycolaldehyde is detected in interstellar medium toward IRAS 16293-2422 and in precometary ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., PNAS, 2015), confirming its cosmochemical prevalence. In the cyanosulfidic framework, glycolaldehyde also forms directly from HCN photoredox (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolaldehyde to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I) cyanide complexes", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide complexes", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (254 nm), H2S as reductant, phosphate buffer"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) undergoes UV-driven photoreduction in the Cu(I)/H2S system. The hydroxyl group at C1 is reduced: the C-OH bond is reductively cleaved, replacing OH with H to yield acetaldehyde (CH3CHO). This is a Kiliani\u2013Fischer-type reductive deoxygenation driven by the same Cu photoredox cycle that generates formaldehyde from HCN.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 2013) demonstrated that the Cu(I)/H2S/UV system reduces glycolaldehyde to acetaldehyde as part of the reductive homologation series. Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) showed this reaction is integral to the cyanosulfidic network, linking sugar chemistry to amino acid precursor synthesis. Acetaldehyde is a critical branch point: it leads to alanine (directly via Strecker) or to threonine (via cyanohydrin \u2192 lactaldehyde)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mild base (phosphate buffer)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9 favors cyanohydrin formation; rapid equilibrium reaction; nucleophilic CN\u207b attacks electrophilic carbonyl"}, "mechanism": "Under mildly basic conditions, HCN deprotonates to form cyanide ion (CN\u207b), which acts as a nucleophile attacking the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde. The resulting alkoxide is protonated to yield acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile, 2-hydroxypropanenitrile, CH3CH(OH)CN). This is a well-characterized, rapid equilibrium reaction that drives toward product at pH 7-9.", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin formation is a standard and rapid reaction well-known in prebiotic chemistry. Ritson & Sutherland (Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 2013) used this reaction as an intermediate step: acetaldehyde cyanohydrin is the direct precursor to lactaldehyde via photoreduction. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds spontaneously in aqueous HCN solutions containing aldehydes. Phosphate buffer maintains optimal pH (Patel et al., Nature Chemistry, 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I) cyanide complexes", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide complexes", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (254 nm), H2S as reductant, 2 hours irradiation achieves 19% yield; produces racemic lactaldehyde"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (C\u2261N) of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (CH3CH(OH)CN) is photoreduced to an aldehyde via the Cu(I)/H2S/UV system. The cyanide carbon is reduced: C\u2261N \u2192 CH=NH (imine) \u2192 CHO (aldehyde upon hydrolysis), yielding lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal, CH3CH(OH)CHO). This is the same photoredox mechanism as rxn_003 and rxn_005 but applied to a nitrile substrate.", "reasoning": "Ritson & Sutherland (Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 2013) demonstrated this specific reaction experimentally, achieving 19% yield of lactaldehyde after 2 hours UV irradiation. This is the key step that generates the threonine-specific aldehyde precursor from the more general cyanosulfidic network. Lactaldehyde is the most direct aldehyde precursor to threonine via Strecker synthesis. The yield of 19% is notable for a prebiotically plausible photochemical reaction."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals, Ca(OH)2", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline conditions; borate stabilizes the glyceraldehyde product through cis-diol complexation; second step of formose-type homologation"}, "mechanism": "Base-catalyzed aldol condensation: glycolaldehyde enolizes under alkaline conditions, and the resulting enolate attacks formaldehyde at its carbonyl carbon. The aldol product is glyceraldehyde (HOCH2CH(OH)CHO). Borate minerals complex the 1,2-diol moiety of glyceraldehyde, stabilizing it against retro-aldol cleavage and further condensation. This is the second step of Kiliani\u2013Fischer homologation in the formose pathway.", "reasoning": "Glyceraldehyde is central to Sutherland's ribonucleotide synthesis and simultaneously connects to threonine via Strecker chemistry (Patel et al., Nature Chemistry, 2015). Borate stabilization of glyceraldehyde is supported by Ricardo et al. (Science, 2004). The aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde is a well-established formose reaction step. Islam, Bu\u010dar & Powner (Nature Chemistry, 2017) showed that 2-aminothiazole can selectively sequester glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from complex mixtures."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9; sequential imine formation then CN\u207b addition; produces racemic mixture of threonine aminonitrile and allothreonine aminonitrile diastereomers (~1:1 ratio)"}, "mechanism": "Classical Strecker synthesis in two steps: (1) lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 to form an imine (CH3CH(OH)CH=NH) with loss of water; (2) cyanide ion (from HCN) attacks the electrophilic imine carbon to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile (threonine aminonitrile). The reaction proceeds through a Schiff base intermediate. Both threonine and allothreonine diastereomeric aminonitriles form in approximately equal amounts because the C3 stereocenter of lactaldehyde is not selectively controlled, and the new C2 stereocenter forms without stereoselection.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) demonstrated that the threonine aminonitrile is one of four amino acid precursors (alongside glycine, alanine, and serine precursors) that arise as 'inevitable by-products' of the cyanosulfidic network. The Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde is the most direct and experimentally validated route to the threonine carbon skeleton. Ritson & Sutherland (2013) established the complete pathway from HCN to lactaldehyde; the subsequent Strecker step is classical aqueous-phase chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9; glyceraldehyde undergoes Strecker at C1 aldehyde; produces threonine aminonitrile and allothreonine aminonitrile as racemic diastereomeric mixture"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde (HOCH2CH(OH)CHO) reacts with NH3 to form an imine at C1, followed by HCN addition to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile. Note: this reaction involves formal reduction and loss of the terminal hydroxymethyl group, or alternatively proceeds through a rearrangement. In the Patel et al. framework, glyceraldehyde serves as an alternative aldehyde entry point that directly generates the threonine aminonitrile scaffold, connecting sugar and amino acid chemistry through a shared C3 intermediate.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2015) explicitly identified glyceraldehyde as a parallel entry point: 'glyceraldehyde (rather than lactaldehyde) provides a second entry point: glyceraldehyde + NH3 + HCN directly yields the threonine aminonitrile.' This convergence is significant because glyceraldehyde is also the key intermediate in ribonucleotide synthesis, meaning amino acid and RNA precursor chemistry share the same starting materials. This represents the deepest connection between the two polymer systems."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "Mild aqueous conditions; nitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide intermediate; pH 4-7 accelerates hydrolysis; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine mixture. Must occur at low temperature to prevent thermal decomposition of product (Truong et al. 2019 showed threonine is among least stable amino acids)."}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis proceeds in two steps: (1) nucleophilic addition of water to the C\u2261N bond yields an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide); (2) further hydrolysis cleaves the C-N(amide) bond to yield the free carboxylic acid (threonine) and ammonia. Under mildly acidic conditions (pH 4-7), both steps proceed at moderate rates at 300-340K without catalysts.", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the final step of the Strecker synthesis and proceeds spontaneously in aqueous solution. This is the terminal reaction in the cyanosulfidic pathway to threonine. Importantly, this step must occur at relatively low temperatures: Truong et al. (Icarus, 2019) established that threonine cannot persist beyond 1 billion years even at 0\u00b0C due to its labile \u03b2-hydroxyl group enabling rapid \u03b2-elimination. This thermal instability strongly constrains the final steps to low-temperature environments."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_005", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ammonium carbonate (from NH3 + CO2)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8-10; (NH4)2CO3 provides both NH3 and CO2 sources; hydantoin forms as thermodynamic sink product, more stable than aminonitrile; wet-dry cycling may concentrate reactants"}, "mechanism": "The Bucherer-Bergs reaction proceeds via: (1) lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin (lactaldehyde cyanohydrin); (2) cyanohydrin + NH3 \u2192 aminonitrile; (3) aminonitrile + CO2 \u2192 carbamoylamino nitrile; (4) intramolecular cyclization \u2192 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin. The hydantoin ring is a thermodynamic sink, making the overall reaction more favorable than stopping at the aminonitrile stage. Ammonium carbonate serves as the source of both NH3 and CO2.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (Nature Chemistry, 2022) demonstrated the Bucherer-Bergs pathway for amino acid synthesis, showing that \u03b1-keto acids convert to amino acids via hydantoin intermediates and that the chemistry parallels extant biosynthetic pathways. For threonine, lactaldehyde would form 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin. Hydantoins have been detected in carbonaceous chondrites (Lerner & Cooper, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta, 2005), providing extraterrestrial evidence for this pathway operating on meteorite parent bodies."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydantoin hydrolysis to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-10; hydantoin ring opens via hydrolysis at both C=O positions; may require moderate heating or prolonged contact with water; produces racemic threonine + allothreonine"}, "mechanism": "Hydantoin hydrolysis proceeds through sequential ring-opening: first hydrolysis at C4 yields N-carbamoyl-threonine (ring-opened intermediate), then decarboxylation and hydrolysis of the remaining urea linkage yields free threonine + CO2 + NH3. The reaction is driven by the thermodynamic stability of the amino acid product relative to the hydantoin under aqueous conditions.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti et al. (Nature Chemistry, 2022) demonstrated that hydantoin hydrolysis to amino acids proceeds under mild prebiotic conditions, completing the Bucherer-Bergs pathway. The hydantoin serves as a protected, stable form of the amino acid that can accumulate and subsequently release threonine upon hydrolysis. This pathway provides an alternative to direct Strecker synthesis that avoids the thermodynamically less favorable aminonitrile intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "native iron (Fe0) and iron-nickel alloys", "aqueous": true, "other": "Strongly reducing conditions; Fe0 serves as both catalyst and reductant; formate is the initial CO2 reduction product that undergoes further reduction to formaldehyde; product must be rapidly transported to cooler zones to prevent over-reduction"}, "mechanism": "Formate (HCOO\u207b) adsorbs on native iron surfaces. Fe0 serves as a two-electron donor, reducing formate through a surface-bound formyl intermediate (HCO*) to formaldehyde (HCHO). The reaction is thermodynamically driven by the oxidation of Fe0 \u2192 Fe2+ (highly exergonic). On mackinawite surfaces, H2 can also provide reducing equivalents via heterolytic splitting. The formaldehyde product must be rapidly removed from the hot zone to avoid further reduction to methanol.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (Nature Ecology & Evolution, 2020) demonstrated that native metals (Fe, Ni, and Fe-Ni alloys) catalyze CO2 fixation to formate and further reduced C1 species under simulated hydrothermal conditions. The stepwise reduction CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 methanol follows decreasing oxidation state and is thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing conditions (low fO2) of Hadean hydrothermal systems. Herschy et al. (Journal of Molecular Evolution, 2014) showed similar chemistry in alkaline vent simulations. This reaction connects hydrothermal CO2 fixation (rxn_001) to the formaldehyde hub that feeds surface cyanosulfidic chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Miller-Urey spark discharge synthesis of acetaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["electrical discharge (lightning)", "volcanic aerosols"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K (post-discharge aqueous phase)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electrical discharge provides activation energy; H2S enhances hydroxylated product yields", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing atmosphere (CH4/NH3/H2O/H2S); spark discharge generates radical species and reactive intermediates in gas phase; products dissolve in aqueous surface pools; H2S atmosphere specifically promotes threonine-relevant hydroxylated intermediates"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge through a CH4/NH3/H2O/H2S gas mixture generates reactive radical species (CH3\u2022, CN\u2022, NH2\u2022, OH\u2022, HS\u2022). Radical recombination and subsequent reactions produce HCN, aldehydes (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), and other reactive intermediates. These dissolve in the aqueous phase where Strecker synthesis occurs spontaneously. H2S promotes formation of hydroxylated species through thiol-mediated radical chemistry. The process is a one-pot generation of the key feedstocks (HCN, acetaldehyde) for subsequent threonine synthesis.", "reasoning": "Parker, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin & Bada (PNAS, 2011) analyzed Miller's unreported 1958 H2S-containing spark discharge experiment (CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S) and detected 23 amino acids including threonine \u2014 which appeared in the H2S experiment but not in other configurations. The H2S atmosphere specifically promoted hydroxylated amino acid production. Johnson et al. (Science, 2008) found Miller's volcanic apparatus produced 22 amino acids including hydroxylated species. Ring, Wolman, Friedmann & Miller (PNAS, 1972) first confirmed threonine and allothreonine detection in spark discharge products. The mechanism proceeds via in situ Strecker synthesis of the dissolved discharge products."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full cyanosulfidic pathway via acetaldehyde-lactaldehyde-Strecker", "description": "The primary experimentally validated route from Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). HCN is photoreduced to formaldehyde via Cu(I)/H2S/UV, dimerized to glycolaldehyde, photoreduced to acetaldehyde, converted to cyanohydrin by HCN, photoreduced to lactaldehyde (19% yield), then Strecker synthesis with NH3/HCN yields threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine. All surface-environment UV photochemistry until final hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanosulfidic pathway via glyceraldehyde branch", "description": "Alternative cyanosulfidic route where glycolaldehyde undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to yield glyceraldehyde instead of photoreduction to acetaldehyde. Glyceraldehyde + NH3 + HCN directly yields threonine aminonitrile, connecting sugar and amino acid chemistry. This branch point is critical as glyceraldehyde is also the entry to Sutherland's ribonucleotide synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde \u2192 cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde-Strecker", "description": "Formaldehyde is produced by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite under hydrothermal conditions (400-500K), transported to surface via hydrothermal fluid circulation, then enters the cyanosulfidic pathway at the glycolaldehyde synthesis step. Demonstrates Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical environmental flow.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde \u2192 cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde-Strecker", "description": "Two-step hydrothermal carbon fixation: CO2 is first reduced to formate on greigite, then formate is further reduced to formaldehyde on native iron. Formaldehyde enters the surface cyanosulfidic pathway. This is the longest pathway, demonstrating full Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical environmental chain.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_014", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route", "description": "Follows the cyanosulfidic pathway to lactaldehyde (as in P1), but diverges at lactaldehyde into the Bucherer-Bergs reaction with HCN + NH3 + CO2 to form a hydantoin thermodynamic sink intermediate, which then hydrolyzes to threonine. The hydantoin intermediate is more stable than the aminonitrile, providing a reservoir for threonine accumulation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde branch", "description": "Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde feeds into the glyceraldehyde branch: formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine. Combines hydrothermal carbon fixation with the sugar-amino acid crossover point at glyceraldehyde.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde branch", "description": "Full hydrothermal CO2 fixation chain (CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde) feeding into the glyceraldehyde Strecker route. The longest glyceraldehyde-based pathway, demonstrating maximum environmental interconnection.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_014", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs", "description": "Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde enters the cyanosulfidic pathway and is channeled through the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route rather than direct Strecker aminonitrile hydrolysis. Combines hydrothermal entry with the thermodynamically favored hydantoin pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Full hydrothermal chain \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs route", "description": "Maximum-length pathway from CO2 through two hydrothermal reduction steps, into surface cyanosulfidic chemistry, through the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin branch. Demonstrates the most complete environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal CO2 fixation \u2192 Hydrothermal formate reduction \u2192 Surface photochemistry \u2192 Biochemical hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_014", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Miller-Urey spark discharge \u2192 lactaldehyde-Strecker route", "description": "Spark discharge on CH4/NH3/H2O/H2S atmosphere generates acetaldehyde and HCN directly (Parker et al. 2011). Acetaldehyde enters the cyanohydrin \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine aminonitrile \u2192 threonine pathway. This bypasses the formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde cyanosulfidic chain, providing an independent atmospheric entry to the acetaldehyde hub. H2S atmosphere specifically enhances hydroxylated amino acid yields.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_015", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_014"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Formaldehyde \u2014 primary C1 hub receiving input from three independent sources (cyanosulfidic photoredox, hydrothermal FTT, hydrothermal formate reduction) and feeding all downstream pathways", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_014"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_008"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Glycolaldehyde \u2014 C2 branch point where formose/aldol chemistry diverges to either acetaldehyde (cyanosulfidic photoreduction, leading to lactaldehyde route) or glyceraldehyde (aldol with formaldehyde, connecting sugar and amino acid chemistry)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "Acetaldehyde \u2014 C2 hub receiving input from both cyanosulfidic photoreduction and Miller-Urey spark discharge, feeding exclusively into the cyanohydrin \u2192 lactaldehyde branch", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_015"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Lactaldehyde \u2014 threonine-specific C3 aldehyde hub and the key divergence point between Strecker synthesis (\u2192 aminonitrile \u2192 threonine) and Bucherer-Bergs (\u2192 hydantoin \u2192 threonine). 19% yield from cyanohydrin photoreduction is the rate-limiting step.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Threonine aminonitrile \u2014 penultimate intermediate receiving convergent input from two Strecker routes (lactaldehyde-based and glyceraldehyde-based), feeding into final hydrolysis. This is the key convergence where the two cyanosulfidic branches (acetaldehyde\u2192lactaldehyde vs. formaldehyde\u2192glyceraldehyde) reunite.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 488168.97320747375, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T20:48:22.689645", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network generates threonine through 10 distinct pathways grounded in the experimentally validated cyanosulfidic framework (Ritson & Sutherland 2013, Patel et al. 2015), Miller-Urey spark discharge chemistry (Parker et al. 2011), and the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway (Pulletikurti et al. 2022). The network is anchored by three formaldehyde-producing entry points: (1) HCN photoredox on Cu minerals at the surface, (2) Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite in hydrothermal vents, and (3) hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate followed by further reduction on native iron. Formaldehyde is the primary hub, feeding into glycolaldehyde, which branches to either acetaldehyde (en route to lactaldehyde via cyanohydrin photoreduction) or glyceraldehyde. Both lactaldehyde and glyceraldehyde undergo Strecker synthesis to yield threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine. An alternative Bucherer-Bergs route through a hydantoin intermediate provides a thermodynamic sink pathway. A tenth pathway enters via spark discharge production of acetaldehyde. All abiotic routes produce racemic threonine/allothreonine diastereomer mixtures (~25% L-threonine). Threonine's documented thermal instability (half-life <1 Gyr at 0\u00b0C; Truong et al. 2019) constrains the network to low-temperature surface and biochemical environments for final steps.\n\nMOLECULES (17 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen gas) [starting]\n  - mol_003: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_005: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_006: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_007: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CHOO- (formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H5NO (acetaldehyde cyanohydrin (lactonitrile)) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C3H6O2 (lactaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H6O3 (glyceraldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H8N2O (threonine aminonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C5H8N2O3 (5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C4H9NO3 (threonine) [target]\n  - mol_017: CH4 (methane) [starting]\n\nREACTIONS (15 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_008 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_003, mol_004, mol_006 -> mol_007 (Cyanosulfidic photoredox synthesis of formaldehyde from HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_007 -> mol_009 (Aldol dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_009, mol_004 -> mol_010 (Cyanosulfidic photoreduction of glycolaldehyde to acetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_010, mol_003 -> mol_011 (Cyanohydrin formation from acetaldehyde and HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_011, mol_004 -> mol_012 (UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_009, mol_007 -> mol_013 (Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_012, mol_005, mol_003 -> mol_014 (Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_013, mol_005, mol_003 -> mol_014 (Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_014, mol_006 -> mol_016 (Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_012, mol_003, mol_005, mol_001 -> mol_015 (Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_015, mol_006 -> mol_016 (Hydantoin hydrolysis to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_014: mol_008, mol_002 -> mol_007 (Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde on native iron) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_015: mol_017, mol_005, mol_006, mol_004 -> mol_010, mol_003 (Miller-Urey spark discharge synthesis of acetaldehyde and HCN) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Full cyanosulfidic pathway via acetaldehyde-lactaldehyde-Strecker (7 steps)\n  - P2: Cyanosulfidic pathway via glyceraldehyde branch (5 steps)\n  - P3: Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde \u2192 cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde-Strecker (7 steps)\n  - P4: Hydrothermal CO2\u2192formate\u2192formaldehyde \u2192 cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde-Strecker (8 steps)\n  - P5: Cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route (7 steps)\n  - P6: Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde branch (5 steps)\n  - P7: Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde branch (6 steps)\n  - P8: Hydrothermal FTT formaldehyde \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs (7 steps)\n  - P9: Full hydrothermal chain \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs route (8 steps)\n  - P10: Miller-Urey spark discharge \u2192 lactaldehyde-Strecker route (5 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_007, mol_009, mol_010, mol_012, mol_014\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of threonine: routes, evidence, and unsolved puzzles\n\n**Threonine emerges as one of the most prebiotically accessible yet paradoxically fragile proteinogenic amino acids.** The cyanosulfidic chemistry developed by Sutherland and colleagues demonstrates that threonine's Strecker precursor forms as an \"inevitable by-product\" of the same HCN photoredox chemistry that generates ribonucleotide building blocks \u2014 linking amino acid and RNA origins in a single reaction network (Patel et al., *Nature Chemistry*, 2015). Yet threonine's \u03b2-hydroxyl group renders it among the least stable amino acids under prebiotic conditions, unable to persist beyond **1 billion years even at 0\u00b0C** in aqueous solution (Truong et al., *Icarus*, 2019). This tension between facile synthesis and rapid degradation defines threonine's unique position in origin-of-life chemistry and frames the central challenge: not how to make it, but how to use it before it decomposes.\n\n---\n\n## Five demonstrated routes from simple molecules to threonine\n\nMultiple independent pathways connect simple prebiotic feedstocks (HCN, NH\u2083, H\u2082O, H\u2082S, CH\u2084, UV light) to threonine. Each proceeds through distinct intermediates and operates under different environmental conditions, suggesting that threonine could have formed in diverse early Earth settings.\n\n### Route 1: Strecker synthesis via lactaldehyde (cyanosulfidic pathway)\n\nThe most completely characterized route proceeds through **lactaldehyde** (2-hydroxypropanal) as the key aldehyde precursor. Ritson and Sutherland (*Angewandte Chemie International Edition*, 2013) demonstrated each step experimentally: UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide complexes with H\u2082S as reductant converts HCN to formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde through photoredox cycling. Acetaldehyde reacts with HCN to form acetaldehyde cyanohydrin, which undergoes photoreduction to lactaldehyde at **19% yield** after 2 hours of irradiation. Lactaldehyde then undergoes classic Strecker chemistry \u2014 reaction with NH\u2083 to form an imine, followed by HCN addition to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutyronitrile (the threonine aminonitrile), which hydrolyzes to threonine and allothreonine as a racemic mixture of diastereomers. The complete pathway requires only HCN, H\u2082O, H\u2082S, Cu minerals, and UV light \u2014 all prebiotically plausible.\n\nPatel et al. (*Nature Chemistry*, 2015) placed this route within the broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism, showing that the threonine aminonitrile is one of four amino acid precursors (alongside those for glycine, alanine, and serine) that arise as \"inevitable by-products\" of the Kiliani\u2013Fischer reductive homologation of HCN that also produces ribonucleotide precursors. A parallel route through glyceraldehyde (rather than lactaldehyde) provides a second entry point: glyceraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN directly yields the threonine aminonitrile.\n\n### Route 2: Miller-Urey spark discharge synthesis\n\nElectric discharge experiments have confirmed threonine production from simple gas mixtures. **Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller** (*Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, 1972) provided the first confirmed detection, using spark discharge on CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O with traces of NH\u2083. Both threonine and allothreonine were identified by ion-exchange chromatography and GC-MS, alongside over 20 other amino acids. The mechanism proceeds through in situ generation of HCN, NH\u2083, and aldehydes (including lactaldehyde) followed by aqueous Strecker synthesis.\n\nReanalysis of Stanley Miller's archived experimental samples revealed additional threonine detections. Parker, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin, and Bada (*PNAS*, 2011) analyzed Miller's unreported 1958 H\u2082S-containing experiment (CH\u2084/NH\u2083/CO\u2082/H\u2082S gas mixture) and detected **23 amino acids including threonine** \u2014 which appeared in the H\u2082S experiment but not in the three other discharge configurations (original, volcanic, silent). The presence of H\u2082S apparently promoted formation of hydroxylated and sulfur-containing amino acids. Johnson et al. (*Science*, 2008) found that Miller's volcanic apparatus (incorporating hot water mist) preferentially synthesized hydroxylated compounds, with **22 amino acids** total. All products were racemic, confirming abiotic origin.\n\n### Route 3: Aldol condensation of glycine and acetaldehyde\n\nThe biological retro-aldol cleavage of threonine (catalyzed by threonine aldolases) yields glycine + acetaldehyde. The reverse \u2014 aldol condensation of glycine with acetaldehyde \u2014 represents a conceptually simple prebiotic route, since both glycine and acetaldehyde rank among the most abundant prebiotic molecules. However, this condensation is **thermodynamically unfavorable** and requires either high glycine concentrations or catalytic assistance to proceed (Fesko, *Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology*, 2016). Both threonine and allothreonine diastereomers form. No purely prebiotic demonstration of this specific aldol condensation has been reported, though the reaction defines the structural relationship between threonine and its simplest precursors.\n\nKoga and Naraoka (*ACS Earth and Space Chemistry*, 2022) demonstrated a related pathway: \u00b9\u00b3C-labeled aldehydes (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde) reacting with ammonia in aqueous solution produced families of **hydroxy amino acids including C\u2083 and C\u2084 structural isomers** that match the distribution found in CM and CR carbonaceous chondrites. This ammonia-aldehyde chemistry provides a route to threonine-related compounds without requiring HCN.\n\n### Route 4: Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids\n\nThe keto acid precursor to threonine is **2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate** (\u03b1-keto-\u03b2-hydroxybutyrate). Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (*Nature*, 2019) demonstrated that Fe\u00b2\u207a promotes reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids at 70\u00b0C, producing glycine, alanine, aspartate, and glutamate from their corresponding keto acids. Kaur et al. (*Chem*, 2024) extended this to H\u2082-driven reductive amination over nickel catalysts at **22\u00b0C and pH 8**. While threonine's specific keto acid precursor was not tested in either study, the principle is established. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Science*, 2006) demonstrated CO-dependent formation of \u03b1-hydroxy and \u03b1-amino acids (including the serine analog, bearing a HOCH\u2082 substituent) at 80\u2013120\u00b0C on Ni-Fe precipitates, suggesting that the threonine homolog (bearing a CH\u2083CHOH substituent) could form via the same chain-elongation mechanism.\n\n### Route 5: Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway\n\nThe Bucherer-Bergs reaction (aldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 + CO\u2082 \u2192 hydantoin \u2192 amino acid) provides a thermodynamic advantage over direct Strecker synthesis because the hydantoin intermediate acts as a thermodynamic sink. Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (*Nature Chemistry*, 2022) demonstrated this pathway for several \u03b1-keto acids \u2192 amino acids, showing that pyruvate converts to alanine via 5-methylhydantoin and that the chemistry parallels extant biosynthetic pathways. For threonine, lactaldehyde would react with HCN and ammonium carbonate to form 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin, which hydrolyzes to threonine. Hydantoins have been detected in carbonaceous chondrites (Lerner and Cooper, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*, 2005), consistent with this pathway operating in meteorite parent bodies.\n\n---\n\n## Critical intermediates and their roles as branch points\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of threonine intersects with several other biosynthetic pathways through shared intermediates, creating a network rather than a linear sequence.\n\n**Lactaldehyde** (2-hydroxypropanal) is the most direct aldehyde precursor specific to threonine via Strecker chemistry. It forms through UV photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin at 19% yield (Ritson and Sutherland, 2013). **Glycolaldehyde** serves as the crucial branch point between sugar chemistry and amino acid chemistry \u2014 it enters the formose reaction to produce ribose precursors and simultaneously provides the carbon skeleton for serine (via Strecker) and connects to threonine through further homologation. Its detection in the interstellar medium toward IRAS 16293-2422 and in precometary ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., *PNAS*, 2015) confirms its cosmochemical availability. **Glyceraldehyde** occupies the next node: it is central to Sutherland's ribonucleotide synthesis and directly reacts with HCN and NH\u2083 to form the threonine aminonitrile, making it perhaps the single most important branch point connecting RNA and protein precursor chemistry.\n\n**Acetaldehyde** connects to threonine through two routes \u2014 Strecker synthesis (producing alanine directly, or lactaldehyde via cyanohydrin reduction, then threonine) and aldol condensation with glycine. It is among the simplest and most abundant products of spark discharge experiments and interstellar chemistry. **\u03b1-Ketobutyrate** represents the metabolic connection: in modern biochemistry, threonine dehydratase converts threonine to \u03b1-ketobutyrate, and the reverse (reductive amination) constitutes a plausible prebiotic route. Copley, Smith, and Morowitz (*PNAS*, 2005) proposed that \u03b1-keto acids formed esters with dinucleotides in a proto-metabolic amino acid synthesis, providing selectivity through nucleotide-keto acid interactions. **HCN oligomers** represent a less specific but broad-spectrum source: Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano, and Osuna-Esteban (*Life*, 2013) reviewed 24 experimental conditions and found that **12 of the 20 proteinogenic amino acids**, including threonine, were detected in HCN polymer hydrolysates, with glycine and aspartic acid consistently the most abundant products.\n\n---\n\n## Environmental settings and their suitability for each synthetic step\n\nDifferent prebiotic environments favor different steps in threonine synthesis, and no single setting optimizes the entire pathway. This \"conditions compatibility problem\" is a central challenge.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** (Lost City type, 40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311) provide the most favorable thermodynamic conditions for amino acid synthesis. Shock and Canovas (*Science*, 1998) calculated that autotrophic synthesis of all 20 amino acids is exergonic in hot, moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions. White, Bhartia, and Russell (*Earth and Planetary Science Letters*, 2015) demonstrated that mackinawite (FeS) and greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) precipitate in simulated Hadean chimney walls at 40\u201380\u00b0C, with maximum greigite yield at 75\u00b0C. Greigite's Fe\u2084S\u2084 cubane units are structural analogs of active centers in modern hydrogenase and ferredoxin. Lane and Martin (*Journal of Molecular Evolution*, 2012) showed that Fe(Ni)S minerals in alkaline vent micropores could concentrate organics approximately **5,000-fold** via thermophoresis, partially addressing the concentration problem.\n\n**Surface volcanic hot springs and evaporitic pools** favor condensation reactions and UV-driven photochemistry. Damer and Deamer (*Astrobiology*, 2020) proposed that volcanic hot spring pools with wet-dry cycling at 60\u201380\u00b0C drive peptide and RNA-like polymer formation. The cyanosulfidic chemistry of Sutherland operates optimally in surface UV-exposed pools with phosphate buffer at ~35\u00b0C. Lahav, White, and Chang (*Science*, 1978) showed that wet-dry cycling plus temperature cycling in clay environments produces longer oligopeptides in higher yields than temperature fluctuations alone. Campbell et al. (*Nature Communications*, 2019) demonstrated that deliquescent minerals can mediate autonomous wet-dry cycling via humidity changes, achieving **over 10-fold higher oligomerization yields**.\n\n**Black smoker hydrothermal vents** (250\u2013400\u00b0C) are problematic. Bada, Miller, and Zhao (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1995) demonstrated that amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C**. However, the mixing zones where hot fluid encounters cold seawater (100\u2013150\u00b0C) remain viable. Marshall (*Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*, 1994) synthesized amino acids at 200\u2013275\u00b0C from aqueous NH\u2084HCO\u2083 with hydrocarbons, though no synthesis occurred below 150\u00b0C. The synthesis-destruction balance is precarious: Aubrey et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2009) concluded that equilibrium at high temperatures favors net degradation rather than synthesis.\n\n**Ice environments** offer a counterintuitive advantage. Eutectic freezing concentrates solutes in brine channels between ice crystals. Miyakawa et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2002) froze NH\u2084CN solutions for 25 years at -20\u00b0C and -78\u00b0C, producing adenine, guanine, and amino acids \u2014 demonstrating that cold environments can drive prebiotic chemistry while simultaneously protecting labile products from thermal degradation.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts accelerate and direct threonine-relevant reactions\n\nMineral surfaces play three critical roles in prebiotic amino acid chemistry: catalyzing bond formation, concentrating dilute reactants, and potentially inducing chiral selectivity.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** anchor W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Science*, 1998) demonstrated peptide formation from amino acids activated by CO on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces at 100\u00b0C, achieving dipeptide yields of **0.4\u201312.4%** and tripeptide yields of ~0.10%. Their 2006 work (*Science*) showed CO-dependent \u03b1-amino acid synthesis on Ni-Fe precipitates at 80\u2013120\u00b0C using cyano ligands as the C/N source. Pyrite (FeS\u2082) shows particularly interesting photocatalytic properties: a 2024 study in *Nature Communications* demonstrated that natural pyrite produces D-amino acids with enantiomeric excess of **14.5\u201342.4%** via asymmetric photocatalytic reductive amination \u2014 the first demonstration of a mineral surface generating significant chiral bias in amino acid synthesis. Cody, Boctor, and Hazen (*Science*, 2000) showed that carbonylated iron-sulfur compounds produce pyruvate from CO and FeS at hydrothermal conditions, establishing the availability of key \u03b1-keto acid precursors.\n\n**Clay minerals**, particularly montmorillonite, catalyze condensation and polymerization. Ferris et al. (*Nature*, 1996) achieved RNA oligomers up to 50 nucleotides on montmorillonite surfaces. For amino acids, Kitadai et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2015) showed that glycine on montmorillonite at 150\u00b0C for 336 hours converts **~13.9% of monomers** to peptides under dry conditions, with no peptides forming without the mineral. Montmorillonite's interlayer structure provides steric effects that enhance condensation while protecting macromolecules from thermal decomposition. Bujd\u00e1k et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1995) demonstrated hetero-oligomerization (ala-gly-gly from ala + gly\u2082) on Ca-montmorillonite during wet-dry cycling at 80\u00b0C, with approximately 10% oligomer yields after 3 weeks.\n\n**Photocatalytic minerals** offer UV-driven synthesis pathways. ZnS surfaces drive reversible reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids (Wang et al., *Chemical Communications*, 2012), supporting Mulkidjanian's zinc world hypothesis (*Biology Direct*, 2009) that life emerged at photosynthetically active porous ZnS structures. TiO\u2082 has been shown to catalyze amino acid production from simple precursors under near-UV illumination (Dunn, Aikawa, and Bard, *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, 1981). Both minerals could have driven amino acid synthesis in shallow, UV-exposed prebiotic pools.\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic and experimental evidence establishes threonine's abiotic credentials\n\nThe detection of threonine in extraterrestrial materials provides independent confirmation that abiotic synthesis occurs under natural conditions, though contamination complicates interpretation.\n\nThe strongest evidence for indigenous extraterrestrial threonine comes from the **CR2 chondrite GRA 95229** (Graves Nunataks, Antarctica). Pizzarello et al. (*PNAS*, 2012) positively identified threonine and allothreonine alongside other hydroxy amino acids, with the critical observation that **threonine was racemic** \u2014 consistent with abiotic synthesis and ruling out biological contamination. The pristine Antarctic collection conditions and the absence of L-excess make this the most compelling meteoritic detection. In the Murchison meteorite, threonine has been detected at approximately **700 ppb** for L-threonine, but the strong L-enrichment (~99% Lee) is attributed to terrestrial contamination (Kato et al., *Scientific Reports*, 2017; Glavin et al., *Meteoritics and Planetary Science*, 2020). Similarly, Tagish Lake analyses showed ~99% Lee for threonine (Glavin et al., 2012), again flagged as contamination. Only **12 of the 20 proteinogenic amino acids** have been confirmed in meteorites with indigenous signatures.\n\nInterstellar ice analog experiments provide complementary evidence. Nuevo et al. (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2008) tentatively detected threonine in organic residues from vacuum UV irradiation of ice mixtures (H\u2082O, CO, CO\u2082, CH\u2083OH, CH\u2084, NH\u2083) at 10\u201380 K \u2014 the first such detection in ice photolysis experiments. Separately, UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene + H\u2082O + NH\u2083 ice at 15 K produced 13 amino acids including threonine (Nuevo et al., *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*, 2008). These experiments demonstrate that threonine can form through non-aqueous photochemistry in interstellar environments.\n\nQuantitative yields from laboratory experiments remain low. In spark discharge experiments, threonine appears at trace levels relative to glycine (the dominant product). Weber (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1998) achieved 0.08% homoserine (threonine's biosynthetic precursor) from formaldehyde + glycolaldehyde + NH\u2084Cl with thiol catalyst at 40\u00b0C over 35 days. The cyanosulfidic pathway achieves 19% yield for the lactaldehyde intermediate, but overall threonine yields through the complete Strecker sequence remain unquantified in the published literature.\n\n---\n\n## Stereochemistry creates a fourfold selectivity challenge\n\nThreonine's two chiral centers (C2 and C3) generate four stereoisomers \u2014 L-threonine (2S,3R), D-threonine (2R,3S), L-allothreonine (2S,3S), and D-allothreonine (2R,3R) \u2014 creating challenges beyond those faced by amino acids with a single stereocenter. Abiotic Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde produces roughly equal amounts of threonine and allothreonine diastereomers, each as a racemic D/L mixture, yielding approximately 25% of the biologically relevant L-threonine. Schroeder and Bada (*Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*, 1977) studied threonine epimerization kinetics in fossil foraminifera and showed that L-threonine epimerizes to D-allothreonine at the \u03b1-carbon faster than \u03b2-carbon racemization, meaning the diastereomer ratio shifts more rapidly than the enantiomeric ratio.\n\nPotential mechanisms for generating enantiomeric excess include **circularly polarized light (CPL)** from star-forming regions, which can induce 1\u20132% ee in amino acids through preferential photodestruction (Modica et al., *Astrophysical Journal*, 2014). This small seed can be amplified: Breslow demonstrated that as little as **1% Lee can reach 95:5 L:D ratio** through simple evaporation, exploiting differential solubility of racemic versus enantiopure crystals. Pyrite's asymmetric photocatalysis (14.5\u201342.4% ee for D-amino acids) represents a mineral-based alternative. However, for threonine specifically, aqueous alteration on meteorite parent bodies promotes racemization of amino acids with \u03b1-hydrogen atoms, meaning any original ee would erode over geological timescales.\n\n---\n\n## Stability, concentration, and the fundamental bottlenecks\n\nThreonine faces several interrelated challenges that constrain its prebiotic accumulation and utilization.\n\n**Thermal instability** is the most severe constraint. Threonine's \u03b2-hydroxyl group enables rapid \u03b2-elimination yielding dehydroaminobutyric acid, analogous to serine's well-characterized decomposition. K\u00f6rner (*ChemSusChem*, 2021) noted that **no systematic investigation of threonine decomposition products under hydrothermal conditions had been performed** as of that date \u2014 a remarkable gap. What is known places threonine among the most labile proteinogenic amino acids: in dry heating studies (80\u2013180\u00b0C), it ranks below most nonpolar and acidic amino acids in stability. Truong et al. (*Icarus*, 2019) established that threonine and aspartic acid cannot persist beyond 1 billion years at 273 K, making them the least durable proteinogenic amino acids \u2014 critical for both origin-of-life scenarios and biosignature detection on icy ocean worlds like Europa and Enceladus.\n\nThe **concentration problem** applies broadly to prebiotic amino acids but affects threonine acutely given its instability. At estimated prebiotic ocean concentrations of ~10\u207b\u2074 M glycine, Ba\u00fa et al. calculated that \"tens of thousands of terrestrial prebiotic oceans would not have sufficed to obtain a single Gly\u2089 molecule at equilibrium.\" Solutions include mineral surface adsorption (layered double hydroxides can concentrate, align, and template amino acids per Erastova et al., *Nature Communications*, 2017), eutectic freezing in ice channels, evaporitic pool concentration via wet-dry cycling, thermophoretic concentration in hydrothermal micropores (~5,000-fold per Lane and Martin), and aerosol chemistry at air-water interfaces.\n\nThe **selectivity problem** \u2014 producing threonine specifically rather than complex mixtures \u2014 remains largely unsolved. The cyanosulfidic pathway offers the most promising selectivity through its constrained reaction network, but still produces mixtures. Islam, Bu\u010dar, and Powner (*Nature Chemistry*, 2017) demonstrated that 2-aminothiazole selectively sequesters glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from complex mixtures, potentially providing a physicochemical selection mechanism. The **water problem** (condensation reactions disfavored in aqueous solution, with \u0394G \u2248 +3.5 kcal/mol for glycine dimerization) applies to subsequent peptide incorporation. Proposed solutions include wet-dry cycling, depsipeptide intermediates (ester bonds formed first, then converted to amides), thioester chemistry, and aminonitrile coupling in water (Canavelli, Islam, and Powner, *Nature*, 2019).\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThreonine's prebiotic synthesis is better understood than for most proteinogenic amino acids, primarily thanks to the cyanosulfidic framework that connects its formation to the same chemistry producing RNA precursors. The Ritson-Sutherland pathway through lactaldehyde provides a complete, experimentally validated route from HCN to the threonine aminonitrile using only prebiotically available materials. Spark discharge experiments confirm that electrical energy acting on simple gas mixtures \u2014 particularly those containing H\u2082S \u2014 produces threonine alongside dozens of other amino acids. Racemic threonine in the pristine CR2 meteorite GRA 95229 demonstrates that abiotic synthesis occurs naturally in asteroid parent bodies.\n\nThree critical gaps remain. First, threonine's thermal and hydrolytic instability means it must be synthesized and utilized on timescales shorter than its decomposition half-life \u2014 a constraint that strongly favors lower-temperature environments (alkaline vents, surface pools, ice) over high-temperature hydrothermal settings. Second, the systematic study of threonine decomposition products under prebiotic conditions has never been performed, leaving the kinetics and products of its degradation poorly constrained. Third, achieving the stereochemical selectivity needed to produce predominantly L-threonine (one of four stereoisomers) from racemic abiotic synthesis remains an open problem, though pyrite's asymmetric photocatalysis and CPL-seeded amplification mechanisms offer partial solutions. The convergence of cyanosulfidic chemistry, meteorite analysis, and mineral catalysis research is steadily narrowing these gaps, positioning threonine as a tractable case study for understanding how biological amino acids emerged from prebiotic chemistry.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.90,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.93,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"