ted (threonine, acetaldehyde, HCN, glycine) are arbitrary selections from a far more complex mixture. Threonine yield in spark discharge is trace-level. The reaction is labeled 'Surface' but spark discharge is atmospheric - the environmental classification is imprecise.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Break into at least 2-3 steps: gas-phase radical chemistry \u2192 aqueous Strecker\", \"Classify initial step as atmospheric rather than surface\", \"Note that threonine is a minor product among >20 amino acids\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.95,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.92,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.90,\n            \"feedback\": \"This is the best pathway for demonstrating hydrothermal \u2192 surface environmental flow. CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite (rxn_001) is well supported by White et al. 2015. Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron (rxn_004) then feeds into the cyanosulfidic surface chemistry. The environmental transition from hydrothermal vent to UV-exposed surface pool is geologically plausible (vent fluid discharge to shallow waters). Both hydrothermal reactions specify mineral catalysts (greigite, native iron). The longest pathway at 8 steps but each step is well-justified.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Could