xn_004) then feeds into the cyanosulfidic surface chemistry. The environmental transition from hydrothermal vent to UV-exposed surface pool is geologically plausible (vent fluid discharge to shallow waters). Both hydrothermal reactions specify mineral catalysts (greigite, native iron). The longest pathway at 8 steps but each step is well-justified.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Could note transport mechanism from hydrothermal to surface environment", "Consider whether formaldehyde survives transit (volatile, reactive)"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.75, "rxn_008": 0.85, "rxn_007": 0.72, "rxn_013": 0.85, "rxn_014": 0.85}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.78, "pathway_coherence": 0.8, "environmental_progression": 0.82, "target_achievement": 0.82, "overall_confidence": 0.8, "feedback": "Reasonable pathway combining FTT synthesis with formose chemistry. rxn_002 (CO + H\u2082 \u2192 formaldehyde on magnetite) is plausible but formaldehyde is not the primary FTT product - methanol and longer hydrocarbons are more typical. The formose reaction (rxn_008) is well-established but notoriously unselective, and glycolaldehyde is a minor product in uncontrolled formose systems. The rxn_007 issue persists here. Still, the hydrothermal \u2192 surface flow is good.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_007"], "suggestions": ["Address formose reaction selectivity - how is glycolaldehyde enriched?", "Consider borate stabilization of sugars (Ricardo et al. 2004)"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_021": 0.68, "rxn_009": 0.85, "rxn_018": 0.8, "rxn_019": 0.78}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.76, "pathway_coherence": 0.75, "environmental_progression": 0.78, "target_achievement": 0.78, "overall_confidence": 0.77, "feedback": "The reductive amination route via Muchowska-Moran Fe\u00b2\u207a chemistry is conceptually sound. However, rxn_021 (CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 glyoxylic acid) is the weakest link - 